# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asida
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The **Abbasid Caliphate** or **Abbasid Empire** was the third Islamic caliphate, ruled by the Abbasid dynasty.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The dynasty was descended from Muhammad's uncle, Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib (d.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids rose to power in 750, when the Abbasid Revolution overthrew the preceding Umayyad Caliphate, and they ruled as caliphs from their metropole in Iraq until 1258, with Baghdad as their capital for most of their history.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasid Revolution had its origins and first successes in the easterly region of Khurasan, far from the Levantine center of Umayyad influence.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids first centered their government in Kufa, Iraq, but in 762 the second caliph al-Mansur founded the city of Baghdad and made it the capital.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Baghdad became a center of science, culture, arts, and invention, ushering in what became known as the Golden Age of Islam.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It hosted several key academic institutions, such as the House of Wisdom, as well as a multi-ethnic and multi-religious population, which made the city famous as a centre of learning across the world.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasid period was marked by the use of bureaucrats in government, including the vizier, as well as a growing inclusion of non-Arab Muslims in the *ummah* (Muslim community) and among the political elites.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The height of Abbasid power and prestige is traditionally associated with the reign of Harun al-Rashid (r.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After his death, a civil war brought new divisions and was followed by significant changes to the character of the state, including the creation of a new professional army recruited mainly from Turkic slaves and the construction of a new capital, Samarra, in 836.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The 9th century also saw many provinces becoming increasingly autonomous, giving rise to local dynasties that controlled different regions of the empire, such as the Aghlabids, Tahirids, Samanids, Saffarids, and Tulunids.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After a period of turmoil in the 860s, the caliphate regained some stability and its seat returned to Baghdad in 892.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During the 10th century, the caliphs were reduced to mere figureheads, with real political and military power resting in the hands of the Iranian Buyids and the Seljuq Turks, who took control of Baghdad in 945 and 1055, respectively.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids eventually regained control of Iraq during the reign of Caliph al-Muqtafi (r.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1136–1160) and extended their rule into Iran during the reign of Caliph al-Nasir (r.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This revival ended in 1258 with the sack of Baghdad by the Mongols under Hulagu Khan and the execution of Caliph al-Musta'sim, which marked the effective end of the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] A surviving branch of the Abbasid dynasty was formally reinstated in 1261 by the Mamluk sultans in Cairo, but it lacked any political power.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The dynasty continued to claim symbolic authority until the Ottoman conquest of Egypt in 1517, the last Abbasid caliph being al-Mutawakkil III.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasid caliphs descended from Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib, one of the youngest uncles of Muhammad and of the same Banu Hashim clan.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This family relation to Muhammad made them appealing to those who were discontented with the rule of the Umayyad caliphs (661–750), who did not descend from the same family.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Over the course of their rule, the Umayyads even suppressed several rebellions that attempted to bring other members of Muhammad's family to power.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] One of the claims that the Abbasids made in the early years of their political movement was that Abu Hashim, the son of Muhammad ibn al-Hanafiyya and grandson of Ali, had formally transferred the Imamate (*imāmah*) to Muhammad ibn Ali (the great-grandson of Abbas) and thus to the Abbasid family.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Muhammad ibn Ali began to campaign in Persia for the return of power to the family of Muhammad, the Hashemites, in the context of the reign of Umar II.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Later, after they had attained power and needed to broaden their support among Muslims, the Abbasids supplemented this claim with other claims to justify their legitimacy.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids also distinguished themselves from the Umayyads by attacking their moral character and administration in general.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids also appealed to non-Arab Muslims, known as *mawali*, who remained outside the kinship-based society of the Arabs and were perceived as a lower class within the Umayyad empire.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] According to Ira Lapidus, "The Abbasid revolt was supported largely by Arabs, mainly the aggrieved settlers of Merv with the addition of the Yemeni faction and their Mawali".
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During the reign of Marwan II, this opposition culminated in the rebellion of Ibrahim al-Imam, the fourth in descent from Abbas.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Supported by the province of Khurasan (eastern Iran), even though the governor opposed them, and the Shi'i Arabs, he achieved considerable success, but was captured and died in prison in 749.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] On 9 June 747 (15 Ramadan AH 129), Abu Muslim, rising from Khurasan, successfully initiated an open revolt against Umayyad rule, which was carried out under the sign of the Black Standard.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Close to 10,000 soldiers were under Abu Muslim's command when the hostilities officially began in Merv.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] General Qahtaba followed the fleeing governor Nasr ibn Sayyar west defeating the Umayyads at the Battle of Gorgan, the Battle of Nahavand and finally in the Battle of Karbala, all in the year 748.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Ibrahim was captured by Marwan and was killed.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The quarrel was taken up by Ibrahim's brother Abdallah, known by the name of Abu al-'Abbas al-Saffah, who defeated the Umayyads in 750 in the battle near the Great Zab river and was subsequently proclaimed caliph.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After this loss, Marwan fled to Egypt, where he was subsequently killed.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The remainder of his family, barring one male, were also eliminated.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 750–754) was spent consolidating Abbasid rule over the Muslim community.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Soon after the victory of 750, Abu Muslim sent forces to Central Asia to confront an army from Tang China led by Gao Xianzhi.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Gao Xianzhi and his army were defeated in 751 at the Battle of Talas, near present-day Tashkent, by the Abbasid army under Ziyad ibn Salih.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This defeat marked the end of Tang influence in Transoxiana and halted Tang westward expansion.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids then consolidated their rule in Transoxania.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Elsewhere, the Abbasids focused on putting down numerous rebellions in Syria and Iraq.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Byzantines conducted raids during these early distractions.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] One of the first major changes effected by Abbasid rule was the move of the caliphate's center of power from Syria to Iraq.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This was closer to the Persian *mawali* support base of the Abbasids and the move addressed their demand for reduced Arab dominance in the empire.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] However, no definitive capital was yet selected.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In these early Abbasid years, Kufa generally served as the administrative capital, but the caliphs were wary of the Alid sympathies in the city and did not always reside here.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 752, al-Saffah built a new city called al-Hashimiyya, at an uncertain location, most likely near Kufa.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Later that same year, he moved to Anbar, where he built a new settlement for his Khurasani soldiers and a palace for himself.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It was al-Saffah's successor, Abu Ja'far al-Mansur (r.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 754–775) who firmly consolidated Abbasid rule and faced down internal challenges.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] His uncle, Abdallah ibn Ali, the victor over the Umayyads at the Battle of the Zab, was the most serious potential rival for leadership and al-Mansur sent Abu Muslim, the Khurasani revolutionary commander, against him in 754.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After Abu Muslim successfully defeated him, al-Mansur then turned to eliminate Abu Muslim himself.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He arranged to have him arrested and executed in 755.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] On the western frontier, the Abbasids were unable to re-assert caliphal control over the western and central Maghreb, which the Umayyads had lost in the 740s.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] One member of the Umayyad dynasty, Abd ar-Rahman, also managed to escape the purge of his family and established independent rule in al-Andalus (present-day Spain and Portugal) in 756, founding the Umayyad emirate of Córdoba.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 756, al-Mansur had also sent over 4,000 Arab mercenaries to assist the Tang dynasty against the rebel leader An Lushan.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids, or "Black Flags" as they were commonly called, were known in Tang dynasty chronicles as the *hēiyī Dàshí*, "The Black-robed Tazi" (黑衣大食) ("Tazi" being a borrowing from Persian *Tāzī*, the word for "Arab").
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Later, Caliph Harun al-Rashid sent embassies to China and established good relations with the Tang emperors.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After the war, these embassies remained in China and al-Rashid established an alliance with China.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Several embassies from the Abbasid caliphs to the Chinese court have been recorded in the *Old Book of Tang*, the most important being those of al-Saffah, al-Mansur, and Harun al-Rashid.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 762, al-Mansur suppressed a rebellion in the Hejaz led by al-Nafs al-Zakiyya, a descendant from Ali ibn Abi Talib, whose challenge to the Abbasid claim to leadership was based on his Alid lineage and thus presented a serious political threat.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He was defeated by an Abbasid army led by Isa ibn Musa.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It was after this victory, in 762, that al-Mansur finally established a proper Abbasid capital, Baghdad – officially called *Madinat al-Salam* ('City of Peace') – located on the Tigris River, near the former ancient capital city of Ctesiphon.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Prior to this, he had continued to consider multiple sites for a capital, including al-Hashimiyya, which he used as a capital for a while, and al-Rumiyya (near the ruins of Ctesiphon), which he used for a few months.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Various other sites in the region also appear to have served as "capitals" under either al-Saffah or al-Mansur prior to the founding of Baghdad.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mansur centralised the judicial administration and, later, Harun al-Rashid established the institution of Great Qadi to oversee it.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Umayyad empire was mostly Arab; however, the Abbasids progressively became made up of more and more converted Muslims in which the Arabs were only one of many ethnicities.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids had depended heavily on the support of Persians in their overthrow of the Umayyads.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mansur welcomed non-Arab Muslims to his court.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] While this helped integrate Arab and Persian cultures, it alienated many of their Arab supporters, particularly the Khurasani Arabs who had supported them in their battles against the Umayyads.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It was also during this early period of the dynasty, in particular during the rule of al-Mansur, Harun al-Rashid, and al-Ma'mun, that its reputation and power were created.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The position of *wazir* (vizier) developed in this period.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It was initially akin to a secretary, but under the tenure of the Barmakids, an Iranian family close to the Abbasids, the position became powerful and Harun al-Rashid delegated state affairs to them for many years.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This resulted in a more ceremonial role for many Abbasid caliphs compared with caliphal rule under the Umayyads; the viziers began to exert greater influence, and the role of the caliph's aristocracy was slowly replaced by a Barmakid bureaucracy.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] At the western end of the empire, Harun al-Rashid agreed to grant the province of Ifriqiya (centered in present-day Tunisia) as a hereditary emirate to Ibrahim ibn al-Aghlab, who founded the Aghlabid dynasty there.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 786–809), the Abbasid Empire reached its peak.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 775–785), restarted the fighting with the Byzantines, and his sons continued the conflict until Empress Irene pushed for peace.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After several years of peace, Nikephoros I broke the treaty, then fended off multiple incursions during the first decade of the 9th century.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] These Abbasid attacks pushed into the Taurus Mountains, culminating with a victory at the Battle of Krasos and the massive invasion of 806, led by al-Rashid himself.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Harun al-Rashid's navy also proved successful, taking Cyprus.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Rashid then focused on the rebellion of Rafi ibn al-Layth in Khurasan and died while there.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Domestically, al-Rashid pursued policies similar to those of his father al-Mahdi.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He released many of the Umayyads and Alids his brother al-Hadi (r.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 785–786) had imprisoned and declared amnesty for all political groups of the Quraysh.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] While Baghdad remained the official capital, al-Rashid chose to reside in Raqqa from 796 until the end of his reign.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 802, he established an unusual succession plan which decreed that his son al-Amin would inherit the title of Caliph and have control of Iraq and the western empire while his other son al-Ma'mun would rule Khurasan and most eastern parts of the empire.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 803, he turned on and imprisoned or killed most of the Barmakids, who had wielded administrative power on his behalf.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The reasons for this sudden and ruthless move remain unclear and have been the subject of much discussion by contemporary writers and later historians.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Rashid's decision to split the succession proved to be damaging to the longevity of the empire.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After his death in 809, his succession pact eventually collapsed and the empire was split by a civil war between al-Amin in Iraq and al-Ma'mun in Khurasan.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This ended with a successful siege of Baghdad by al-Ma'mun's forces.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] When the city fell in 813, al-Amin was captured and executed on the orders of al-Ma'mun's general, Tahir ibn Husayn.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This marked the first time that an Abbasid ruler was publicly executed and it irrevocably damaged the prestige of the caliphate.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Ma'mun became caliph and ruled until his death in 833.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He initially ruled the empire from his established base in Merv, Khurasan, where his main support was found, but this prolonged the discontent and instability in Iraq and triggered further fighting in the years following his victory.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 817, he officially declared an Alid, 'Ali al-Rida, as his heir, instead of an Abbasid family member, perhaps hoping to promote Muslim unity, but the move backfired.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Eventually, he was compelled to step back from these policies and move his court to Baghdad, where he arrived in August 819.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After this, the rest of his reign was relatively peaceful.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Exceptions included a rebellion in Azerbaijan by the Khurramites, supported by the Byzantines, which continued until 837.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He also repulsed a Byzantine attack on Syria around 829, followed by counter-attacks into Anatolia, and suppressed a rebellion in Egypt in 832.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The later years of al-Ma'mun's reign are known for his intellectual interests and patronage.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The so-called "translation movement" — the state-sponsored translation of scientific and literary works of antiquity into Arabic — that had begun under his predecessors was pushed even further during this time and al-Ma'mun shifted its focus to ancient Greek works of science and philosophy.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In matters of religion, his interest in philosophy spurred him to endorse Mu'tazilism, the rationalist school of Islamic thought.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Under its influence, he officially endorsed the doctrine of createdness of the Qur'an in 827.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 833, he went further and forcibly imposed it on the *ulama*, the Sunni religious scholars.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This controversial policy, known as the *Mihna*, was eventually abandoned in 848.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Ultimately, it failed to convince the Sunni *ulama* and instead contributed to the emergence of the latter as a more cohesive social class whose views and interests did not always align with the caliph.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Following the civil war between al-Amin and al-Ma'mun, the traditional mainstay of the Abbasid army, the *Khurasaniyya* and *'Abna al-dawla*, were no longer seen as reliable and the caliphs sought to recruit a new type of army whose loyalty could be better assured.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This process began under al-Ma'mun but it is his brother and successor, al-Mu'tasim (r.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 833–842), who is known for its more radical implementation.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Soldiers were recruited from several new sources, but the most important, especially under al-Mu'tasim, were the group referred to by Arabic chronicles as "Turks" (*atrāk*), who appear to have been mainly Turkic people from Central Asia.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Some modern scholars refer to them as Mamluks, marking them as the antecedent of the later slave-soldiers known by that term, but their exact legal status has been a subject of scholarly debate.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Many, perhaps the majority, were originally purchased or captured slaves, but they were paid regular salaries and thus likely manumitted.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In any case, these outsiders did not have political ties among the traditional elites and thus their loyalty was to the caliph alone.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] These troops were likely the first standing army of the caliphate and provided the caliph with a strong base of military support.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] However, the influx of new foreign troops into the capital created tensions with its inhabitants and with older elites.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This was one of the main reasons why, in 836, al-Mu'tasim decided to found a new capital, Samarra, on an open site to the north of Baghdad.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The new capital housed the caliph's army, allowed for the unhindered construction of massive new palaces, and became the focus of an even more elaborate courtly culture.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mu'tasim's reign marked the end of the strong caliphs.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He strengthened his personal army with the Mamluks and promptly restarted the war with the Byzantines.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Though his attempt to seize Constantinople failed when his fleet was destroyed by a storm, his military excursions were generally successful, culminating with a resounding victory in the Sack of Amorium.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] From the ninth century onward, the Abbasids found they could no longer keep together a centralized polity from Baghdad, which had grown larger than that of Rome.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] As mentioned, Harun al-Rashid had already granted the province of Ifriqiya to the Aghlabids, who ruled this region as an autonomous vassal state until its fall to the Fatimids in 909.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In al-Ma'mun's reign, Tahir ibn Husayn (al-Ma'mun's general in the civil war) was appointed viceroy of Iran and most of the eastern regions of the empire from 821 onward.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] His descendants, the Tahirids, continued to govern in this position with significant autonomy until 873, although they remained loyal to the caliph and used only the title of *amir*.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] From their capital at Nishapur, they were important patrons of Arabic literature and Sunni religious scholarship, in addition to making major improvements to agriculture.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In Transoxiana, the Persian Samanids of Bukhara and Samarkand ruled as local governors, initially under the Tahirids.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They oversaw the development of the region's cities into major trade centers, profiting from long-distance trade between China, Central Asia, Eastern Europe, and the Middle East.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 847–861) was characterized by the caliph's extravagant spending, his attempts to further consolidate power within the state, and his replacement of the *Mihna* policy with support for more orthodox Sunni scholars, in particular the Hanbali school.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 853, the Byzantines sacked Damietta in Egypt, and the caliph responded by sending troops into Anatolia, who sacked and marauded until they were eventually annihilated in 863.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mutawakkil's lifestyle and spending weakened his support among the military.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 861, he was murdered at a party by a group of Turkish soldiers.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This was the first time the Abbasid military intervened so directly and violently at court and it set a precedent for further coups.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The following period, sometimes known as the "Anarchy at Samarra" (861–870), saw four different caliphs come and go.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] While they each attempted to reassert their authority, they were at the mercy of military and political factions.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Tax collection lapsed and, along with al-Mutawakkil's previous spending, this left the state short on funds, which exacerbated the infighting.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 865, the Turkish soldiers of Samarra even besieged Baghdad to overthrow the caliph al-Musta'in and, when the city fell the following year, they replaced him with al-Mu'tazz.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The latter was overthrown by the same faction in 869 and replaced by al-Muhtadi, who was similarly overthrown in 870.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Muhtadi was succeeded by al-Mu'tamid, who was finally able to restore some order, in large part thanks to the help of his brother al-Muwaffaq, who kept the military under control and ran most government affairs.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The restoration was hampered by the Zanj rebellion, which erupted in 869 and threatened the center of Abbasid control in Iraq.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This major threat was not brought under control until a determined campaign was launched in 879.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] By the 870s, Egypt became autonomous under Ahmad ibn Tulun and his Tulunid successors, though they continued to acknowledge the caliph and generally sent tribute to Baghdad.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] For a time, they even controlled Syria and parts of the Jazira (Upper Mesopotamia).
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 882, the caliph al-Mu'tamid even tried to move his residence to Egypt at Ibn Tulun's invitation, though this move was aborted by the intervention of al-Muwaffaq.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In the east, the Saffarids were former soldiers in the Abbasid army who were stationed in Sistan and remained there as local strongmen.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They began to challenge the Tahirids from 854 onward and in 873 they captured Nishapur, ending Tahirid rule.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They marched on Baghdad in 876 but were defeated by al-Muwaffaq.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The two sides were forced to come to terms and the Abbasids allowed the Saffarids to rule over Sistan, Fars, Kirman, and Khurasan.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 898, al-Mu'tadid set the Saffarids and Samanids against each other by formally endorsing a Saffarid claim over Transoxiana, the Samanid domain.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Samanids emerged triumphant in battle and were able to expand their control thenceforth to Khurasan, while the Saffarids were contained further south.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Samanids never threatened Iraq or western Iran, but they were also not as close to the caliphs as their Tahirid predecessors and in practice they were almost entirely independent of Baghdad.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They became even greater patrons of religion and the arts than the Tahirids.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They still maintained an orthodox Sunni ideology but they differed from their predecessors by promoting the Persian language.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] There was a brief Abbasid political and military revival at the end of the 9th century, especially under the policies of caliphs al-Mu'tadid (r.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Under al-Mu'tadid, the capital was moved from Samarra back to Baghdad.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Incursions by the Qarmatians and allied Bedouin tribes posed a serious threat from 899 onwards, but the Abbasid army, led by Muhammad ibn Sulayman, won a reprieve against them in 904 and 907.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 905, the same general invaded Egypt and overthrew the weakened Tulunids, re-establishing Abbasid control to the west.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] By the time caliph al-Muktafi died in 908, the Abbasid revival was at its peak and a strong centralized state was in place again.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After his death, however, the state became dominated by feuding bureaucrats.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 908–932), the Abbasid court continued to project power and wealth publicly but the politics and financial policies of the time compromised the caliphate's sustainability in the long-term.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It was in this period that the practice of giving out *iqta*s (fiefs in the form of tax farms) as favours began, which had the effect of reducing the caliphate's own tax revenues.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 909, North Africa was lost to the Fatimid dynasty, an Isma'ili Shia sect tracing its roots to Muhammad's daughter Fatima.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Fatimids took control of Ifriqiya from the Aghlabids and eventually conquered Egypt in 969, where they established their capital, Cairo, near Fustat.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] By the end of the century, they were one of the main political and ideological challenges to Sunni Islam and the Abbasids, contesting the Abbasids for the titular authority of the Islamic *ummah*.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The challenge of the Fatimid Caliphate only ended with their downfall in the 12th century.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 934–941), Baghdad's authority declined further as local governors refused to send payments to the capital.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Ikhshidids ruled Egypt and Syria autonomously prior to the Fatimid takeover.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Even in Iraq, many governors refused to obey and the caliph was unable to send armies against them.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Radi was forced to invite the governor of Wasit, Muhammad ibn Ra'iq, to take over the administration under the newly created position of *amir al-umara* ("Commander of Commanders").
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Ibn Ra'iq disbanded the salaried army of the caliph and reduced much of the government's bureaucratic infrastructure, including the traditional vizierate, thus removing much of the Abbasid state's basis for power.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He was overthrown in 938 and the following years were bogged down in political turmoil.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mustakfi had a short reign from 944 to 946, and it was during this period that the Persian faction known as the Buyids from Daylam swept into power and assumed control over the bureaucracy in Baghdad.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] According to the history of Miskawayh, they began distributing *iqta*s to their supporters.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This period of localized secular control was to last nearly 100 years.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Mahmud of Ghazni took the title of sultan, as opposed to the *amir* that had been in more common usage, signifying the Ghaznavid Empire's independence from caliphal authority, despite Mahmud's ostentatious displays of Sunni orthodoxy and ritual submission to the caliph.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In the 11th century, the loss of respect for the caliphs continued, as some Islamic rulers no longer mentioned the caliph's name in the Friday *khutba*, or struck it off their coinage.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Despite the power of the Buyid amirs, the Abbasids retained a highly ritualized court in Baghdad, as described by the Buyid bureaucrat Hilal al-Sabi', and they retained a certain influence over Baghdad as well as religious life.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] As Buyid power waned with the rule of Baha' al-Daula, the caliphate was able to regain some measure of strength.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The caliph al-Qadir, for example, led the ideological struggle against the Shia with writings such as the *Baghdad Manifesto*.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The caliphs kept order in Baghdad itself, attempting to prevent the outbreak of *fitna*s in the capital, often contending with the *ayyarun*.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] With the Buyid dynasty on the wane, a vacuum was created that was eventually filled by the dynasty of Oghuz Turks known as the Seljuqs.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] By 1055, the Seljuqs had wrested control from the Buyids and Abbasids, and took temporal power.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] When the amir and former slave Basasiri took up the Shia Fatimid banner in Baghdad in 1056–57, the caliph al-Qa'im was unable to defeat him without outside help.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Toghril Beg, the Seljuq sultan, restored Baghdad to Sunni rule and took Iraq for his dynasty.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Once again, the Abbasids were forced to deal with a military power that they could not match, though the Abbasid caliph remained the titular head of the Islamic community.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The succeeding sultans Alp Arslan and Malikshah, as well as their vizier Nizam al-Mulk, took up residence in Persia, but held power over the Abbasids in Baghdad.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] When the dynasty began to weaken in the 12th century, the Abbasids gained greater independence once again.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1118–1135) was the first caliph to build an army and to lead it in battle since the 10th century.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He recruited Kurdish and Arab Bedouin tribes and re-fortified Baghdad.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] His first concern was not the Seljuks but the Mazyadids of Hilla in central Iraq, whom he met in battle in 1123.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] His bid for independence was ultimately unsuccessful, as he was defeated by a Seljuk army in 1135 and assassinated soon after.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1136–1160), a new caliphal state began to emerge with the help of his vizier Ibn Hubayra.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Ibn Hubayra concentrated on reasserting authority in Iraq while the Seljuk Empire deteriorated.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids successfully defended Baghdad against the Seljuqs in the siege of 1157 and then conquered their Mazyadid enemies in Hilla in 1162.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] By the end of al-Muqtafi's reign, Baghdad controlled a state stretching from Basra in the south to the edges of Mosul in the north.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After over two hundred years of Abbasid subjection to foreign dynasties, Caliph al-Mustanjid (r.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1160–1170) formally declared independence from the Seljuk sultans in 1165, when he dropped their names from Abbasid coinage.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Initially, the caliphs were still vulnerable to the power of the viziers, but al-Mustadi (r.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1170–1180) was able to further rally some support from the Baghdad public as well as symbolic support abroad from the Ayyubid sultan Saladin and the Rum Seljuk sultan Kilij Arslan II.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1180–1225) marked a definitive shift in late Abbasid power.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He reinvigorated public displays of caliphal prestige, removed officials who were too powerful, engaged in diplomacy with regions beyond Iraq, and extended his control over former Seljuk territories in western Iran — including Isfahan, Hamadan, Qazvin and Zanjan.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He sought to build up his influence among Muslim rulers abroad largely through the Sufi-inspired *futuwwa* brotherhood that he headed.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1226–1242), the Abbasid state achieved significant stability and many of the same policies continued.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He built the Mustansiriyya Madrasa, inaugurated in 1234, the first madrasa to teach all four Sunni *maddhab*s (schools of jurisprudence) and the first madrasa commissioned by an Abbasid caliph.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 1206, Genghis Khan established a powerful dynasty among the Mongols of Central Asia.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During the 13th century, this Mongol Empire conquered most of the Eurasian land mass, including both China in the east and much of the old Islamic caliphate and the Kievan Rus' in the west.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 1252, Hulagu Khan, a grandson of Genghis Khan and brother of the new Mongol ruler, Möngke Khan, was placed in charge of a new western campaign to the Middle East that would culminate in the conquest of Baghdad in 1258.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In the years leading up the Mongol invasion, Baghdad's strength was sapped by political rivalries, sectarian tensions between Sunnis and Shias, and damaging floods.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 1257, after destroying the Assassins in Iran, Hulagu wrote to the Abbasid caliph, al-Musta'sim, demanding his submission.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The caliph refused, with Hulagu's status as a non-Muslim (unlike the earlier Buyids and Seljuks) likely a factor.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] There followed months of diplomacy, during which the Mongols may have been informed of Baghdad's weakness by correspondence with the caliph's vizier, Ibn al-Alqami, a Shia who was later accused of colluding with them.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Mongols began their siege of the city on 29 January 1258.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] On 10 February, al-Musta'sim agreed to meet with Hulagu, who demanded that the caliph order the defenders to stand down and come out of the city in exchange for mercy.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The caliph complied, but the Mongols slaughtered the population and then began the sack of the city on 13 February.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Contemporary accounts describe destruction, looting, rape, and killing on a massive scale over many days, with hundreds of thousands killed and the city reduced to near-empty ruins, though some, like the Christian and Shia communities, were spared.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Mongols feared rumours that a supernatural disaster would strike if the blood of al-Musta'sim, a direct descendant of Muhammad's uncle and part of a dynasty that had reigned for five centuries, was spilled.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] As a precaution and in accordance with a Mongol taboo against spilling royal blood, Hulagu had al-Musta'sim wrapped in a carpet and trampled to death by horses on 20 February 1258.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The caliph's immediate family was also executed, with the lone exceptions of his youngest son who was sent to Mongolia and a daughter who became a slave in the harem of Hulagu.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The fall of Baghdad marked the effective end of the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It made a deep impression on contemporary and later writers both inside and outside the Muslim world, some of whom created legendary stories about the last caliph's demise.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It is also traditionally seen as the approximate end to the "classical age" or "golden age" of Islamic civilization.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The events brought profound geopolitical changes to the traditional lands of the Islamic caliphate, with Iraq, Iran, and most of the eastern lands falling under Mongol control while other Muslim rulers retained the lands to the west.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Mongol expansion further west was eventually halted by the Mamluks of Egypt at the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260, followed by the conflict between the Ilkhanids (Hulagu and his successors) and their Golden Horde rivals, which diverted Mongol attention.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Prior to the Mongol invasion, the later Ayyubid sultans of Egypt had built up an army recruited from slaves, the Mamluks.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During a political and military crisis in 1250, the Mamluks seized power and established what is now known as the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Following the devastation of Baghdad in 1258 and in an effort to secure political legitimacy for the new regime in Egypt, the Mamluk ruler Baybars invited a surviving member of the Abbasid family to establish himself in Cairo in 1260–1261.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The new caliph was al-Mustansir II, a brother of the former caliph al-Mustansir.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 1262, he disappeared while leading a small army in an attempt to recapture Baghdad from the Mongols.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Baybars subsequently replaced him with al-Hakim I, another Abbasid family member who had just been proclaimed in Aleppo.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Thereafter, the Abbasid caliphs in Cairo continued to exist as a strictly ceremonial but nonetheless important institution within the Mamluk Sultanate, conferring significant prestige on the Mamluks.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It continued to be relevant even to other Muslim rulers until the 14th century; for example, the sultans of Delhi, the Muzaffarid sultan Muhammad, the Jalayirid sultan Ahmad, and the Ottoman sultan Bayezid I all sought diplomas of investiture from the caliph or declared nominal allegiance to him.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Caliph al-Musta'in even managed to reign as sultan in Cairo for a brief six months in 1412.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During the 15th century, however, the institution of the caliph declined in significance.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The last Abbasid caliph in Cairo was al-Mutawakkil III, who was in place when the Ottoman sultan Selim I defeated the Mamluks in 1516 and conquered Egypt in 1517, ending the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Selim I met with al-Mutawakkil III in Aleppo in 1516, prior to marching into Egypt, and the caliph was then sent to the Ottoman capital of Constantinople (present-day Istanbul), ending the Abbasid caliphate definitively.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids themselves slipped into historical obscurity after this.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The idea of a "caliphate" subsequently became an ambiguous concept that was occasionally revisited by later Muslim rulers and intellectuals for political or religious reasons.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Ottoman sultans, who were thenceforth the most powerful Muslim rulers in western Asia and the Mediterranean, did not use the title of "caliph" at all before the mid-16th century and only did so vaguely and inconsistently afterwards.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The claim that al-Mutawakkil III "transferred" the office of the caliph to the Ottoman sultan during their meeting in Aleppo is a legend that was elaborated in the 19th century and is not corroborated by contemporary accounts.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasid historical period lasting to the Mongol conquest of Baghdad in 1258 CE is considered the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Islamic Golden Age was inaugurated by the middle of the 8th century by the ascension of the Abbasid Caliphate and the transfer of the capital from Damascus to Baghdad.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids were influenced by the Qur'anic injunctions and hadith, such as "the ink of a scholar is more holy than the blood of a martyr", stressing the value of knowledge.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Many classic works of antiquity that would otherwise have been lost were translated into Arabic and Persian and later in turn translated into Turkish, Hebrew and Latin.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During this period the Muslim world was a cauldron of cultures which collected, synthesized and significantly advanced the knowledge gained from the Roman, Chinese, Indian, Persian, Egyptian, North African, Ancient Greek and Medieval Greek civilizations.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Abbasid literary culture in Iraq reflects long-term Mesopotamian narrative continuities, particularly traditions centered on heroic figures and on barriers separating chaos and order.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Core motifs associated with the Epic of Gilgamesh, mediated through the Alexander Romance, including journeys to the world's limits and the containment of chaos, persisted across religious and political change and continued to circulate in late antique Iraq.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Babylonian Talmud, composed by Iraq-based rabbis, preserves parallel traditions concerning Gog and Magog and the imagined edges of the world that confine agents of chaos.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Together, these traditions situate elements of Abbasid literature within a Mesopotamian narrative continuum.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The best-known fiction from the Islamic world is *One Thousand and One Nights*, a collection of fantastical folk tales, legends and parables compiled primarily during the Abbasid era.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The collection is recorded as having originated from an Arabic translation of a Sassanian-era Persian prototype, with likely origins in Indian literary traditions.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Stories from Arabic, Persian, Mesopotamian, and Egyptian folklore and literature were later incorporated.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The epic is believed to have taken shape in the 10th century and reached its final form by the 14th century; the number and type of tales have varied from one manuscript to another.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] All Arabian fantasy tales were often called "Arabian Nights" when translated into English, regardless of whether they appeared in *The Book of One Thousand and One Nights*.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This epic has been influential in the West since it was translated in the 18th century, first by Antoine Galland.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Many imitations were written, especially in France.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Various characters from this epic have themselves become cultural icons in Western culture, such as Aladdin, Sinbad and Ali Baba.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] A famous example of Islamic poetry on romance was *Layla and Majnun*, an originally Arabic story which was further developed by Iranian, Azerbaijani and other poets in the Persian, Azerbaijani, and Turkish languages.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It is a tragic story of undying love much like the later *Romeo and Juliet*.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Arabic poetry reached its greatest height in the Abbasid era, especially before the loss of central authority and the rise of the Persianate dynasties.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Writers like Abu Tammam and Abu Nuwas were closely connected to the caliphal court in Baghdad during the early 9th century, while others such as al-Mutanabbi received their patronage from regional courts.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Under Harun al-Rashid, Baghdad was renowned for its bookstores, which proliferated after the making of paper was introduced.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Chinese papermakers had been among those taken prisoner by the Arabs at the Battle of Talas in 751.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] As prisoners of war, they were dispatched to Samarkand, where they helped set up the first Arab paper mill.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In time, paper replaced parchment as the medium for writing, and the production of books greatly increased.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] These events had an academic and societal impact that could be broadly compared to the introduction of the printing press in the West.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Paper aided in communication and record-keeping, it also brought a new sophistication and complexity to businesses, banking, and the civil service.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 794, Jafa al-Barmak built the first paper mill in Baghdad, and from there the technology circulated.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Harun required that paper be employed in government dealings, since something recorded on paper could not easily be changed or removed, and eventually, an entire street in Baghdad's business district was dedicated to selling paper and books.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] One of the common definitions for "Islamic philosophy" is "the style of philosophy produced within the framework of Islamic culture".
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Islamic philosophy, in this definition is neither necessarily concerned with religious issues, nor is exclusively produced by Muslims.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Their works on Aristotle were a key step in the transmission of learning from ancient Greeks to the Islamic world and the West.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They often corrected the philosopher, encouraging a lively debate in the spirit of ijtihad.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They also wrote influential original philosophical works, and their thinking was incorporated into Christian philosophy during the Middle Ages, notably by Thomas Aquinas.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Three speculative thinkers, al-Kindi, al-Farabi, and Avicenna, combined Aristotelianism and Neoplatonism with other ideas introduced through Islam, and Avicennism was later established as a result.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Other influential Abbasid philosophers include al-Jahiz, and Ibn al-Haytham (Alhacen).
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] As power shifted from the Umayyads to the Abbasids, the architectural styles changed also, from Greco-Roman tradition (which features elements of Hellenistic and Roman representative style) to Eastern tradition which retained their independent architectural traditions from Mesopotamia and Persia.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] A defining characteristic of Abbasid architecture in Iraq was the extensive use of stucco and plaster decoration, particularly in interior spaces.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The limited availability of high-quality building stone in Abbasid Iraq contributed to the widespread use of stucco and other malleable materials, which were well suited to repetitive and abstract ornamental decoration.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] At Samarra, these conditions enabled the emergence of a standardized decorative vocabulary that departed from Late Antique naturalism and proved influential well beyond Iraq.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Color also played an important role, particularly the use of blue pigments to enhance stucco and painted surfaces, intensifying abstraction and, in some contexts, carrying protective or apotropaic associations.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasid architecture was particularly influenced by Sasanian architecture, which in turn featured elements present since ancient Mesopotamia.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Christian styles evolved into a style based more on the Sasanian Empire, utilizing mud bricks and baked bricks with carved stucco.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Other architectural innovations and styles were few, such as the four-centered arch, and a dome erected on squinches.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Unfortunately, much was lost due to the ephemeral nature of the stucco and luster tiles.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Another major development was the creation or vast enlargement of cities as they were turned into the capital of the empire, beginning with the creation of Baghdad in 762, which was planned as a walled city with four gates, and a mosque and palace in the center.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mansur, who was responsible for the creation of Baghdad, also planned the city of Raqqa, along the Euphrates.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Finally, in 836, al-Mu'tasim moved the capital to a new site that he created along the Tigris, called Samarra.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This city saw 60 years of work, with race-courses and game preserves to add to the atmosphere.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Due to the dry remote nature of the environment, some of the palaces built in this era were isolated havens.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Ukhaidir Fortress is a fine example of this type of building, which has stables, living quarters, and a mosque, all surrounding inner courtyards.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Iraq only has one surviving mausoleum from this era, in Samarra: an octagonal domed structure known as the *Qubbat al-Sulaibiyya*, which is the first known monumental tomb in Islamic architecture and may be the final resting place of al-Muntasir.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Baghdad, the epicenter of the empire, was originally organized in a circular fashion next to the Tigris River, with massive brick walls being constructed in successive rings around the core by a workforce of 100,000 with four huge gates (named Kufa, Basra, Khurasan and Syria).
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The central enclosure of the city contained Mansur's palace of 360,000 square feet (33,000 m2) in area and the great mosque of Baghdad, encompassing 90,000 square feet (8,400 m2).
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Travel across the Tigris and the network of waterways allowing the drainage of the Euphrates into the Tigris was facilitated by bridges and canals servicing the population.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Outside the Abbasid heartlands, architecture was still influenced by the capital.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In present-day Tunisia, the Great Mosque of Kairouan was founded under the Umayyad dynasty but completely rebuilt in the 9th century under the patronage of the Aghlabids, vassals of the Abbasids.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The styles utilized were mainly Abbasid.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In Egypt, Ahmad Ibn Tulun commissioned the Ibn Tulun Mosque, completed in 879, that is based on the style of Samarra and is now one of the best-preserved Abbasid-style mosques from this period.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The establishment of Abbasid power based in Iraq, rather than Syria, resulted in a cultural and artistic development influenced not only by the Mediterranean and Middle Eastern traditions but also by connections further afield with India, Central Asia, and China.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The importation of Chinese ceramics elicited local imitations but also stirred innovations in local production.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Abbasid ceramics became a more important art form with greater emphasis on decoration.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] A major innovation was the emergence of monochrome and polychrome lustreware, a technical achievement that had an important impact on the wider development of Islamic ceramics.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Glassware also became a more important art form and was likely the origin of the lustre technique that was introduced into ceramics.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Few textiles have survived but the production of *tiraz*, textiles with royal inscriptions, is well attested.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Another major art form was calligraphy and manuscript production.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During the Abbasid period, Arabic calligraphy evolved into a more refined discipline.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Rounded Kufic script was typical and became increasingly stylized.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Parchment only allowed for a few lines of script, but from the late 8th century onward paper began to be produced.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Qur'ans are the main type of book to have survived from this period.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] A number of medieval thinkers and scientists living under Islamic rule played a role in transmitting Islamic science to the Christian West.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In addition, the period saw the recovery of much of the Alexandrian mathematical, geometric and astronomical knowledge, such as that of Euclid and Claudius Ptolemy.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] These recovered mathematical methods were later enhanced and developed by other Islamic scholars, notably by Persian scientists Al-Biruni and Abu Nasr Mansur.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Christians (particularly Nestorian Christians) contributed to the Arab Islamic Civilization during the Umayyads and the Abbasids by translating works of Greek philosophers to Syriac and afterwards to Arabic.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Nestorians played a prominent role in the formation of Arab culture, with the Academy of Gondishapur being prominent in the late Sassanid, Umayyad and early Abbasid periods.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Notably, eight generations of the Nestorian Bukhtishu family served as private doctors to caliphs and sultans between the eighth and eleventh centuries.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Algebra was significantly developed by Persian scientist Muhammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī during this time in his landmark text, *Kitab al-Jabr wa-l-Muqabala*, from which the term *algebra* is derived.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] He is thus considered to be the father of algebra by some, although the Greek mathematician Diophantus has also been given this title.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The terms *algorism* and *algorithm* are derived from the name of al-Khwarizmi, who was also responsible for introducing the Arabic numerals and Hindu–Arabic numeral system beyond the Indian subcontinent.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Arab scientist Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen) developed an early scientific method in his *Book of Optics* (1021).
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The most important development of the scientific method was the use of experiments to distinguish between competing scientific theories set within a generally empirical orientation, which began among Muslim scientists.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Ibn al-Haytham's empirical proof of the intromission theory of light (that is, that light rays entered the eyes rather than being emitted by them) was particularly important.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Ibn al-Haytham was significant in the history of scientific method, particularly in his approach to experimentation, and has been referred to as the "world's first true scientist".
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Medicine in medieval Islam was an area of science that advanced particularly during the Abbasids' reign.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During the 9th century, Baghdad contained over 800 doctors, and great discoveries in the understanding of anatomy and diseases were made.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The clinical distinction between measles and smallpox was described during this time.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Famous Persian scientist Ibn Sina (known to the West as Avicenna) produced treatises and works that summarized the vast amount of knowledge that scientists had accumulated, and was very influential through his encyclopedias, *The Canon of Medicine* and *The Book of Healing*.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The work of him and many others directly influenced the research of European scientists during the Renaissance.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Astronomy in medieval Islam was advanced by Al-Battani, who improved the precision of the measurement of the precession of the Earth's axis.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The corrections made to the geocentric model by al-Battani, Averroes, Nasir al-Din al-Tusi, Mo'ayyeduddin Urdi and Ibn al-Shatir were later incorporated into the Copernican heliocentric model.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The astrolabe, though originally developed by the Greeks, was developed further by Islamic astronomers and engineers, and subsequently brought to medieval Europe.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Muslim alchemists influenced medieval European alchemists, particularly the writings attributed to Jābir ibn Hayyān (Geber).
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In technology, the Abbasids adopted papermaking from China.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The use of paper spread from China into the caliphate in the 8th century CE, arriving in al-Andalus (Islamic Spain) and then the rest of Europe in the 10th century.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It was easier to manufacture than parchment, less likely to crack than papyrus, and could absorb ink, making it ideal for making records and copies of the Qur'an.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] "Islamic paper makers devised assembly-line methods of hand-copying manuscripts to turn out editions far larger than any available in Europe for centuries." It was from the Abbasids that the rest of the world learned to make paper from linen.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The knowledge of gunpowder was also transmitted from China via the caliphate, where the formulas for pure potassium nitrate and an explosive gunpowder effect were first developed.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Advances were made in irrigation and farming, using new technology such as the windmill.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Crops such as almonds and citrus fruit were brought to Europe through al-Andalus, and sugar cultivation was gradually adopted by the Europeans.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Apart from the Nile, Tigris and Euphrates, navigable rivers were uncommon, so transport by sea was very important.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Navigational sciences were highly developed, making use of a rudimentary sextant (known as a *kamal*).
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] When combined with detailed maps of the period, sailors were able to sail across oceans rather than skirt along the coast.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Abbasid sailors were also responsible for reintroducing large three masted merchant vessels to the Mediterranean.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The name *caravel* may derive from an earlier Arab ship known as the *qārib*.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Arab merchants dominated trade in the Indian Ocean until the arrival of the Portuguese in the 16th century.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Hormuz was an important center for this trade.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] There was also a dense network of trade routes in the Mediterranean, along which Muslim countries traded with each other and with European powers such as Venice or Genoa.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Silk Road crossing Central Asia passed through the Abbasid caliphate between China and Europe.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Engineers in the Abbasid caliphate made a number of innovative industrial uses of hydropower, and early industrial uses of tidal power, wind power, and petroleum (notably by distillation into kerosene).
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The industrial uses of watermills in the Islamic world date back to the 7th century, while horizontal-wheeled and vertical-wheeled water mills were both in widespread use since at least the 9th century.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] By the time of the Crusades, every province throughout the Islamic world had mills in operation, from al-Andalus and North Africa to the Middle East and Central Asia.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] These mills performed a variety of agricultural and industrial tasks.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Abbasid engineers also developed machines (such as pumps) incorporating crankshafts, employed gears in mills and water-raising machines, and used dams to provide additional power to watermills and water-raising machines.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Such advances made it possible for many industrial tasks that were previously driven by manual labour in ancient times to be mechanized and driven by machinery instead in the medieval Islamic world.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It has been argued that the industrial use of waterpower had spread from Islamic to Christian Spain, where fulling mills, paper mills, and forge mills were recorded for the first time in Catalonia.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] A number of industries were generated during the Arab Agricultural Revolution, including early industries for textiles, sugar, rope-making, matting, silk, and paper.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Latin translations of the 12th century passed on knowledge of chemistry and instrument making in particular.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The agricultural and handicraft industries also experienced high levels of growth during this period.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] While the Abbasids originally gained power by exploiting the social inequalities against non-Arabs in the Umayyad Empire, during Abbasid rule the empire rapidly Arabized, particularly in the Fertile Crescent region (namely Mesopotamia and the Levant) as had begun under Umayyad rule.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] As knowledge was shared in the Arabic language throughout the empire, many people from different nationalities and religions began to speak Arabic in their everyday lives.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Resources from other languages began to be translated into Arabic, and a unique Islamic identity began to form that fused previous cultures with Arab culture, creating a level of civilization and knowledge that was considered a marvel in Europe at the time.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In contrast to the earlier era, women in Abbasid society were absent from all arenas of the community's central affairs.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] While their Muslim forebears led men into battle, started rebellions, and played an active role in community life, as demonstrated in the Hadith literature, Abbasid women were ideally kept in seclusion.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Conquests had brought enormous wealth and large numbers of slaves to the Muslim elite.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The majority of the slaves were women and children, many of whom had been dependents or harem-members of the defeated Sassanian upper classes.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In the wake of the conquests an elite man could potentially own a thousand slaves, and ordinary soldiers could have ten people serving them.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Even so, slave courtesans (qiyans and jawaris) and princesses produced prestigious and important poetry.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Enough survives to give us access to women's historical experiences, and reveals some vivacious and powerful figures, such as the Sufi mystic Raabi'a al-Adwiyya (714–801 CE), the princess and poet 'Ulayya bint al-Mahdi (777–825 CE), and the singing-girls Shāriyah (c.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Each wife in the Abbasid harem had an additional home or flat, with her own enslaved staff of eunuchs and maidservants.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] When a concubine gave birth to a son, she was elevated in rank to umm walad and also received apartments and (slave) servants as a gift.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The status and treatment of Jews, Christians, and non-Muslims in the Abbasid Caliphate was a complex and continually changing issue.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Dhimmis faced some level of discrimination in Abbasid society: they did not have all the privileges of Muslims and had to pay jizya, a tax on non-Muslims.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] However, as people of the book (non-Muslim monotheists), Jews and Christians were allowed to practice their religion and were not required to convert.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Ecclesiastical authorities discouraged practices such as polygamy and sought to regulate interreligious unions, yet ordinary Christians in Iraq and neighboring regions nonetheless participated in both Christian and Islamic marital practices and households across confessional lines.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Christian men might take multiple wives or marry non-Christians, and interreligious marriages, especially those involving Muslim husbands and Christian women, were a persistent concern for Christian jurists, who viewed them as threatening communal boundaries.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] One of the common aspects of the treatment of the dhimmis is that their treatment depended on who the caliph was at the time.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Some Abbasid rulers, like Al-Mutawakkil (822–861 CE) imposed strict restrictions on what dhimmis could wear in public, often yellow garments that distinguished them from Muslims.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Other restrictions al-Mutawakkil imposed included limiting the role of the dhimmis in government, seizing dhimmi housing and making it harder for dhimmis to become educated.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Most other Abbasid caliphs were not as strict as al-Mutawakkil.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During the reign of Al-Mansur (754–775 CE), it was common for Jews and Christians to influence the overall culture in the caliphate, specifically in Baghdad.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Jews and Christians did this by participating in scholarly work.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It was common that laws that were imposed against dhimmis during one caliph's rule were either discarded or not practiced during future caliphs' reigns.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Al-Mansur and al-Mutawakkil both instituted laws that forbade non-Muslims from participating in public office.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Al-Mansur did not follow his own law very closely, bringing dhimmis back to the caliphate's treasury due to the needed expertise of dhimmis in the area of finance.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Al-Mutawakkil followed the law banning dhimmis from public office more seriously, although, soon after his reign, many of the laws concerning dhimmis participating in government were completely unobserved or at least less strictly observed.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] 908–932 CE), who held a similar stance as al-Mutawakkil on barring non-Muslims from public office, himself had multiple Christian secretaries, indicating that non-Muslims still had access to many of the most important figures within the caliphate.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Past having a casual association or just being a secretary to high-ranking Islamic officials, some of them achieved the second highest office after the caliph: the vizier.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Jews and Christians may have had a lower overall status compared to Muslims in the Abbasid Caliphate, but dhimmis were often allowed to hold respectable and even prestigious occupations in some cases, such as doctors and public officeholders.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Jews and Christians were also allowed to be rich even if they were taxed for being a dhimmi.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Dhimmis were capable of moving up and down the social ladder, though this largely depended on the particular caliph.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] An indication as to the social standing of Jews and Christians at the time was their ability to live next to Muslim people.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] While al-Mansur was ruling the caliphate, for instance, it was not uncommon for dhimmis to live in the same neighborhoods as Muslims.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] One of the biggest reasons why dhimmis were allowed to hold prestigious jobs and positions in government is that they were generally important to the well-being of the state and were proficient to excellent with the work at hand.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In general, Muslims, Jews, and Christians had close relations that could be considered positive at times, especially for Jews, in contrast to how Jews were being treated in Europe.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Many of the laws and restrictions that were imposed on dhimmis often resembled other laws that previous states had used to discriminate against a minority religion, specifically Jewish people.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Romans in the fourth century banned Jewish people from holding public offices, banned Roman citizens from converting to Judaism, and often demoted Jews who were serving in the Roman military.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In direct contrast, there was an event in which two viziers, Ibn al-Furat and Ali ibn Isa ibn al-Jarrah, argued about Ibn al-Furat's decision to make a Christian the head of the military.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] A previous vizier, Abu Muhammad al-Hasan al-Bazuri, had done so.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] These laws predated al-Mansur's laws against dhimmis and often had similar restrictions, although Roman emperors were often much more strict on enforcing these laws than many Abbasid caliphs.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Most of Baghdad's Jews were incorporated into the Arab community and considered Arabic their native language.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Some Jews studied Hebrew in their schools and Jewish religious education flourished.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The united Muslim empire allowed Jews to reconstruct links between their dispersed communities throughout the Middle East.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The city's Talmudic institute helped spread the rabbinical tradition to Europe, and the Jewish community in Baghdad went on to establish ten rabbinical schools and twenty-three synagogues.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Baghdad not only contained the tombs of Muslim saints and martyrs, but also the tomb of Yusha, whose corpse had been brought to Iraq during the first migration of the Jews out of the Levant.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] There were large feasts on certain days, as the Muslims of the empire celebrated Christian holidays as well as their own.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] There were two main Islamic feasts: one marked by the end of Ramadan; the other, "the Feast of Sacrifice".
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The former was especially joyful because children would purchase decorations and sweetmeats; people prepared the best food and bought new clothes.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] At midmorning, the caliph, wearing Muhammad's thobe, would guide officials, accompanied by armed soldiers to the Great Mosque, where he led prayers.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] After the prayer, all those in attendance would exchange the best wishes and hug their kin and companions.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During those limited number of nights, the palaces were lit up and boats on the Tigris hung lights.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It was said that Baghdad "glittered 'like a bride'".
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During the Feast of Sacrifice, sheep were butchered in public arenas and the caliph participated in a large-scale sacrifice in the palace courtyard.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Afterward, the meat would be divided and given to the poor.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In addition to these two holidays, Shias celebrated the birthdays of Fatimah and Ali ibn Abi Talib.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Matrimonies and births in the royal family were observed by all in the empire.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The announcement that one of the caliph's sons could recite the Koran smoothly was greeted by communal jubilation.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] When Harun developed this holy talent, the people lit torches and decorated the streets with wreaths of flowers, and his father, Al-Mahdi, freed 500 slaves.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Of all the holidays imported from other cultures and religions, the one most celebrated in Baghdad (a city with many Persians) was Nowruz, which celebrated the arrival of spring.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In a ceremonial ablution introduced by Persian troops, residents sprinkled themselves with water and ate almond cakes.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The palaces of the imperial family were lit up for six days and nights.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Abbasids also celebrated the Persian holiday of Mihraj, which marked the onset of winter (signified with pounding drums), and Sadar, when homes burned incense and the masses would congregate along the Tigris to witness princes and viziers pass by.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Abbasid army amassed an array of siege equipment, such as catapults, mangonels, battering rams, ladders, grappling irons, and hooks.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] All such weaponry was operated by military engineers.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] However, the primary siege weapon was the *manjaniq*, a type of siege weapon that was comparable to the trebuchet employed in Western medieval times.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] From the seventh century onward, it had largely replaced torsion artillery.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] By Harun al-Rashid's time, the Abbasid army employed fire grenades.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Abbasids also utilized field hospitals and ambulances drawn by camels.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The cavalry was entirely covered in iron, with helmets.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Similar to medieval knights, their only exposed spots were the end of their noses and small openings in front of their eyes.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Their foot soldiers were issued spears, swords, and pikes, and (in line with Persian fashion) trained to stand so solidly that, one contemporary wrote "you would have thought them held fast by clamps of bronze".
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Although the Abbasids never retained a substantial regular army, the caliph could recruit a considerable number of soldiers in a short time when needed from levies.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] There were also cohorts of regular troops who received steady pay and a special forces unit.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] At any moment, 125,000 Muslim soldiers could be assembled along the Byzantine frontier, Baghdad, Medina, Damascus, Rayy, and other geostrategic locations in order to quell any unrest.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During the Abbasid revolution, Abu Muslim's Khorasani army, composed largely of Arab settlers disillusioned with Umayyad rule, marched under black banners, forming a powerful force that swept westward in open revolt.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In Baghdad there were many Abbasid military leaders who were or said they were of Arab descent.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] However, it is clear that most of the ranks were of Iranian origin, the vast majority being from Khurasan and Transoxiana, not from western Iran or Azerbaijan.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Most of the Khurasani soldiers who brought the Abbasids to power were Arabs.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The standing army of the Muslims in Khurasan was overwhelmingly Arab.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The unit organization of the Abbasids was designed with the goal of ethnic and racial equality among supporters.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] When Abu Muslim recruited officers along the Silk Road, he registered them based not on their tribal or ethno-national affiliations but on their current places of residence.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Under the Abbasids, Iranian peoples became better represented in the army and bureaucracy as compared to before.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] He abolished the old *jund* system created by Umar and diverted the salaries of the original Arab military descendants to the Turkic slave soldiers.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Turkic soldiers transformed the style of warfare, as they were known as capable horse archers, trained from childhood to ride.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] This military was now drafted from the ethnic groups of the faraway borderlands, and were completely separate from the rest of society.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] This led to the decline of the caliphate starting with the Anarchy at Samarra.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] As a result of such a vast Empire, the caliphate was decentralized and divided into 24 provinces.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Harun's vizier enjoyed close to unchecked powers.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Under Harun, a special "bureau of confiscation" was created.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] This governmental wing made it possible for the vizier to seize the property and riches of any corrupt governor or civil servant.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In addition, it allowed governors to confiscate the estates of lower-ranking officials.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Finally, the caliph could impose the same penalty on a vizier who fell from grace.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] As one later caliph put it: "The vizier is our representative throughout the land and amongst our subjects.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Every regional metropolis had a post office and hundreds of roads were paved in order to link the imperial capital with other cities and towns.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The empire employed a system of relays to deliver mail.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The central post office in Baghdad even had a map with directions that noted the distances between each town.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The roads were provided with roadside inns, hospices, and wells and could reach eastward through Persia and Central Asia, to as far as China.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The post office not only enhanced civil services but also served as intelligence for the caliph.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Mailmen were employed as spies who kept an eye on local affairs.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Early in the days of the caliphate, the Barmakids took the responsibility of shaping the civil service.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The family had roots in a Buddhist monastery in northern Afghanistan.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In the early 8th century, the family converted to Islam and began to take on a sizable part of the civil administration for the Abbasids.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Capital poured into the caliphate's treasury from a variety of taxes, including a real estate tax; a levy on cattle, gold and silver, and commercial wares; a special tax on non-Muslims; and customs dues.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Under Harun al-Rashid, maritime trade through the Persian Gulf thrived, with Arab vessels trading as far south as Madagascar and as far east as China, Korea, and Japan.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The growing economy of Baghdad and other cities inevitably led to the demand for luxury items and formed a class of entrepreneurs who organized long-range caravans for the trade and then the distribution of their goods.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] A whole section in the East Baghdad suq was dedicated to Chinese goods.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Much of this direct maritime trade was oriented toward Iraqi markets, particularly Basra and Baghdad, which functioned as major destinations for goods arriving from Tang China.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] From the seventh to the tenth centuries, merchants from the Gulf served Iraqi markets through direct sea routes linking the Persian Gulf to the South China coast, especially Guangzhou, as attested by both contemporary textual sources and archaeological evidence.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The ninth-century Belitung shipwreck, carrying a large cargo of Chinese ceramics, illustrates the scale of this trade and its connection to demand in Iraq and the wider Abbasid realm.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Arabs traded with the Baltic region and made it as far north as the British Isles.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Tens of thousands of Arab coins have been discovered in parts of Russia and Sweden, which bear witness to the comprehensive trade networks set up by the Abbasids.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] King Offa of Mercia (in England) minted gold coins similar to those of the Abbasids in the eighth century.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Muslim merchants employed ports in Bandar Siraf, Basra, and Aden and some Red Sea ports to travel and trade with India and South East Asia.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Land routes were also utilized through Central Asia.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Arab businessmen were present in China as early as the eighth century.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Arab merchants sailed the Caspian Sea to reach and trade with Bukhara and Samarkand.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During the ninth and tenth centuries, large quantities of opaque glazed pottery were produced in southern Iraq, within the heartlands of the Abbasid Caliphate, and exported as a mass-produced commercial commodity.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Finds of this Iraqi ware at sites across the Middle East, South Africa, and Southeast Asia demonstrate sustained commercial interaction between Iraq and the wider Indian Ocean world.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Most of the exported vessels were standardized and practical in design, indicating that they were produced for large-scale commercial trade rather than for elite or luxury use.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Many caravans and goods never made it to their intended destinations.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Some Chinese exports perished in fires, while other ships sank.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It was said that anybody who made it to China and back unharmed was blessed by God.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Common sea routes were also plagued by pirates who built and crewed vessels that were faster than most merchant ships.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It is said that many of the adventures at sea in the Sinbad tales were based on historical fiction of mariners of the day.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Abbasids also established overland trade with Africa, largely for gold and slaves.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] When trade with Europe ceased due to hostilities, Jews served as a link between the two hostile worlds.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Abbasids engaged in extensive trade with the Italian maritime republics of Venice and Genoa, from the 11th century.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Venetian merchants facilitated the exchange of high-value goods such as spices, silk, and precious metals from the East.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In return, Venice exported European manufactured goods and luxury items.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] While Genoese merchants traded in luxury goods like spices, textiles, and other high-demand items.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Genoa's strategic position in the Mediterranean enabled it to integrate into the broader Mediterranean trade network, connecting the Abbasid Caliphate with other European markets.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] These trade relations played a key role in linking the medieval Mediterranean with the broader Islamic world.
[src:asida/abbasid-caliphate-p02] This exchange of goods, alongside cultural and technological transfers, fostered a more interconnected medieval global economy.
[src:asida/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:asida/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:asida/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:asida/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:asida/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:asida/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:asida/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:asida/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:asida/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:asida/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:asida/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:asida/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:asida/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:asida/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:asida/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:asida/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:asida/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:asida/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:asida/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:asida/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:asida/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:asida/acehnese-cuisine] A variety of Acehnese food is cooked with curry or coconut milk, which is generally combined with meat such as buffalo, beef, goat meat, lamb, mutton, fish, or chicken.
[src:asida/acehnese-cuisine] Several Aceh dishes can trace their origins to India, such as roti canai, which was derived from Indian flatbread.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Each region in Africa has developed its own distinctive culinary practices, shaped by local ingredients, colonial history and trade.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In **West Africa,** for example, dishes often feature rice, millet, and beans complemented by spicy stews made with fish, meat, and leafy greens.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The use of chili peppers, peanuts and palm oil is also widespread in this region.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] **Central African** cuisine on the other hand, tends to be simpler and relies heavily on starchy foods such as cassava and plantains, often served with sauces made with peanuts or vegetables.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In **East Africa**, particularly in countries like Kenya, Tanzania, and Uganda, the cuisine reflects a combination of native agricultural practices and influences from trade routes with India and the Middle East.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Staples such as maize, beans, and rice are commonly consumed along with dishes like Ugali (a maize-based porridge) and sukuma wiki (a dish made from collard greens).
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The coastal areas of East Africa, particularly along the Swahili coast, feature seafood and curries seasoned with spices such as cardamom and cloves, a direct influence of Indian and Arab traders.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] **Southern African** cuisine also displays a blend of indigenous ingredients and colonial influences.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Dishes such as pap (a maize-based porridge) and biltong (a type of sausage) are popular in countries like South Africa, Botswana, and Namibia.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The cuisine is characterized by the use of game meat, maize, and beans, as well as European influences introduced during colonial times.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Traditionally, the various **cuisines of Africa** use a combination of plant-and seed-based ingredients, without having food imported.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In some parts of the continent, the traditional diet features an abundance of root tuber products.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Africa represents a rich history of adaptation, trade, and resourcefulness. while regional differences are pronounced, the use of local ingredients and traditional cooking techniques remains central to the continent's culinary identity.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Central Africa, East Africa, North Africa, Southern Africa and West Africa each have distinctive dishes, preparation techniques, and consumption modes.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The roots of native African cuisine goes back to thousands of years before the Bronze Age in Northeast Africa, when early civilizations began cultivating grains such as barley and wheat.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Part of North Africa is in the Fertile Crescent where settled agriculture was practiced by the Ancient Egyptians in this area.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Animals such as donkeys and sheep were also domesticated, starting the spread of agriculture to other parts of Africa, notably West Africa.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Although most tribes still lived a simple hunter-gather diet.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Arab explorers- Leo Africanus and Ibn Battuta- provided accounts of African food which they encountered on their travels through sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Most European travelers stayed close to coastal areas until the 19th century.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Many of their diaries also recorded details on foods and crops.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Many staples were introduced later when Africa was colonized by the Europeans.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Foods that are now important parts of African cuisine such as maize and potatoes were not common until the 19th century.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The influence of African food on Caribbean, Brazilian, American Lowcountry cuisine, and Cajun cuisine from Louisiana is seen in rice dishes and green stews like the Afro-Caribbean efo, duckanoo and callaloo.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The vegetable okra, introduced from Africa, is used in classic Louisiana gumbos, and American rice growing in the Carolina.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Lowcountry was influenced by West African techniques of rice cultivation and many slaves hailed from the rice-growing regions of West Africa.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Lowcountry cuisine is still known for its distinctive rice dishes.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Central Africa expands from the Tibesti Mountains in the north to the vast rainforest basin of the Congo River, the highlands of Kivu and the savannah of Katanga.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] This region has received the culinary influence of the Swahilis (culture that evolved via the combination of Bantu, Yemeni, Omani and Indian cultures) during the trans-Saharan slave trade.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Swahili culinary influences can be found in dishes such as mandazi, pilaf rice, kachumbari, sambusa, and kuku paka.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Central African cuisine has also been influenced by the Portuguese, by way of the Kongo and Ndongo Kingdoms.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Salt fish was introduced following trade in the late 17th century, and the Kikongo term for salt fish, makayabu, comes from the Portuguese term bacalhau.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The Portuguese culinary influence is especially prominent in Angola, Sao Tomé and Equatorial Guinea.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Central Africa has also been influenced by the cuisine of the East, West and Southern Africa regions because of their close proximity, e.g. babuté or bobotie is shared with the south, nyama choma with the east and sauce gombo with West Africa.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In Central Africa, a variety of crops are grown, including yams, cassava, bananas and plantains, sweet potatoes, and cocoyams.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] These crops have become staples in the diet of many people in Central Africa.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Fufu-like starchy foods are usually made from fermented cassava roots, but they can also be made with plantain, corn maize and yam.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Fufu is served buffet-style with grilled meat, fish, stews, greens and piment .
[src:asida/african-cuisine] A variety of local ingredients are used while preparing other dishes, like spinach stew cooked with tomato, peppers, chilies, onions, and peanut butter.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Eastern central Africa is also one of the few regions in Africa that uses potatoes as one of its main bases, since potatoes grow easily in the region.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Cassava plants are also consumed as cooked greens.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Groundnut (peanut) stew is also prepared, containing chicken, okra, ginger, and other spices.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Beef and chicken are favorite meat dishes, but game meat preparations containing crocodile, elephant, antelope and warthog meats are also served occasionally.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The cuisine of East Africa varies from area to area.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In the inland savannah, the traditional cuisine of cattle-keeping peoples is distinctive meaning that meat products are generally absent.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Cattle, sheep, pigs and goats were regarded as a form of currency and a store of wealth.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] They are not generally consumed as food.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In some areas, traditional East Africans consume the milk and blood of cattle, but rarely the meat.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Elsewhere, other Africans are farmers who grow a variety of grains and vegetables.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Maize (corn) is the basis of ugali', the local version of West and Central Africa's fufu.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Ugali is a starch dish eaten with meats or stews.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In Uganda, steamed green bananas called matoke provide the starch filler of many meals.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Around 1000 years ago, Omani and Yemeni merchants settled on the Swahili Coast.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Middle Eastern influences are especially reflected in the Swahili cuisine of the coast—steamed or cooked rice with spices in Persian style; saffron, cloves, cinnamon and several other spices; and pomegranate juice.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Several centuries later, the British and the Indians came, and both brought with them foods such as Indian spiced vegetable curries, lentil soups, chapattis and a variety of pickles which have influenced various local dishes.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Some common ingredients used in this region include oranges, lemons, limes, chilies, capsicum peppers, maize, tomatoes, and strawberries.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In the Horn of Africa, the main traditional dishes in Eritrean cuisine and Ethiopian cuisine are tsebhis (stews) served with injera (flatbread made from teff, wheat, or sorghum) and hilbet (paste made from legumes, mainly lentils and fava beans).
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Eritrean and Ethiopian cuisine (especially in the northern half) are very similar, given the shared history of the two countries.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Eritrean and Ethiopian food habits vary regionally.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In the highlands, injera is the staple diet and is eaten daily among the Tigrinya.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Injera is made out of teff, wheat, barley, sorghum or corn, and resembles a spongy, slightly sour pancake.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] When eating, diners generally share food from a large tray placed in the center of a low dining table.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Many injera are layered on this tray and topped with various spicy stews.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Diners then break into the section of injera in front of them, tearing off pieces and dipping them into the stews.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In the lowlands, the main dish is akelet, a porridge-like dish made from wheat flour dough.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] A ladle is used to scoop out the top, which is filled with berbere and butter sauce and surrounded by milk or yoghurt.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] A small piece of dough is broken and then used to scoop up the sauce.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The best known Ethiopian/Eritrean cuisine consists of various vegetable or meat side dishes and entrées, usually a wat, or thick stew, served atop injera, a large sourdough flatbread made of teff flour.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] One does not eat with utensils, but instead uses injera to scoop up the entrées and side dishes.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Tihlo, prepared from roasted barley flour, is very popular in Amhara, Agame, and Awlaelo (Tigray).
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Traditional Ethiopian cuisine employs no pork or shellfish of any kind, as they are forbidden in the Jewish and Ethiopian Orthodox Christian faiths.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] It is also very common to eat from the same dish in the center of the table with a group of people.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Somali cuisine varies from region to region and consists of an exotic mixture of diverse culinary influences.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] It is the product of Somalia's rich tradition of trade and commerce.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Despite the variety, there remains one thing that unites the various regional cuisines: all food is served halal.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] There are therefore no pork dishes, alcohol is not served, nothing that died on its own is eaten, and no blood is incorporated.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Varieties of bariis (rice), the most popular being basmati, usually serve as the main dish.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Spices like cumin, cardamom, cloves, cinnamon and sage are used to aromatize these different rice dishes.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] During Ramadan, dinner is often served after Tarawih prayers, sometimes as late as 11 pm.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Xalwo (halwo) or halva is a popular confection served during special occasions such as Eid celebrations or wedding receptions.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] It is made from sugar, cornstarch, cardamom powder, nutmeg powder, and ghee.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Peanuts are also sometimes added to enhance texture and flavor.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] After meals, homes are traditionally perfumed using frankincense (lubaan) or incense (cuunsi), which is prepared inside an incense burner referred to as a dabqaad.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Food and nutrition security in East Africa (Rwanda, Burundi and South Sudan) is a significant issue.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The region has been plagued by drought, conflict and economic instability since the 1990s.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The current situation is characterized by low levels of food availability and high levels of malnutrition among young children.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The solution proposed for this problem is to increase local food production.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] This would be achieved by increasing agricultural productivity by improving soil fertility and water management, which will help farmers grow more crops per year.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] This will also help reduce poverty in the region by providing more employment opportunities for local people.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In a study of food loss and waste in North Africa, researchers found that the region was wasting about 30% of its food, which is likely to increase as the population continues to grow.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] This waste occurs for a variety of reasons, including lack of refrigeration and storage facilities.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] To solve this issue, the people had to get creative with new dishes and ways of storing food.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The more we looked, the more we found that people were using all parts of plants in some way—the leaves, stems, flowers, fruits and seeds.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] They also used every edible part of animals as well—from fat to bones for making broth or soup.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] North Africa lies along the Mediterranean Sea and encompasses within its fold several nations, including Morocco, Algeria, Libya, Tunisia, and Egypt.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The roots of North African cuisine can be traced back to the ancient empires of North Africa, particularly in Egypt, where many of the country's dishes and culinary traditions date back to African antiquity.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Over several centuries traders, travelers, invaders, migrants and immigrants all have influenced the cuisine of North Africa.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The Phoenicians of the 1st century brought sausages, while the Carthaginians introduced wheat and its by-product, semolina.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The Berbers adapted semolina into couscous, one of the main staple foods.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Olives and olive oil were introduced before the arrival of the Romans.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] From the 7th century onwards, the Arabs introduced a variety of spices, like saffron, nutmeg, cinnamon, ginger and cloves, which contributed and influenced the culinary culture of North Africa.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The Ottoman Turks brought sweet pastries and other bakery products, and from the New World, North Africa got potatoes, tomatoes, zucchini and chili peppers.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In addition, two completely different dishes may also share the same name (for example, a tajine dish is a slow-cooked stew in Morocco, whereas the Tunisian tajine is a baked omelette/quiche-like dish).
[src:asida/african-cuisine] There are noticeable differences between the cooking styles of different nations, from the sophisticated, full-bodied flavors of Moroccan palace cookery to the fiery dishes of Tunisian cuisine and the humbler, simpler cuisines of Egypt and Algeria.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The cooking of the Southern Africa region (not to be confused with the country of South Africa) is sometimes called "rainbow cuisine", as the food in this region is a blend of many cultures: indigenous African societies, European, and Asian.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] To understand indigenous African cuisine, it is important to understand the various native peoples of southern Africa.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The indigenous Africans of Southern Africa were roughly divided into two groups and several subgroups.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The largest group consisted of the Bantu-speakers, whose descendants today may identify themselves by various subgroup names such as Ndebele (northern and southern), Shona, Venda, Zulu, Xhosa, Swazi, Sotho, Tswana, Pedi and Tsonga.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] They arrived in the region around 2,000 years ago, bringing crop cultivation, animal husbandry, and iron toolmaking with them.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Hence the Bantu-speakers grew grain crops extensively and raised cattle, sheep and goats.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] They also grew and continue to grow pumpkins, beans, and leafy greens as vegetables.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] A smaller group were the primeval residents of the region, the Khoisan, who some archaeologists believe had lived in the region for at least 10,000 years.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Many descendants of the Khoisan people have now been incorporated into the population of South Africa.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The Khoisan originally were hunter-gatherers (who came to be known as "San" by the Bantu-speakers and as "bushmen" by Europeans).
[src:asida/african-cuisine] After the arrival of the Bantu-speakers, however, some Khoisan adopted the Bantu-speakers' raising of cattle but did not grow crops.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] People were, in other words, defined to some extent by the kinds of food they ate.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The Bantu-speakers ate dishes of grain, meat, milk and vegetables, as well as fermented grain and fermented milk products.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] While the Khoi-Khoi ate meat and milk and the San hunted wild animals and gathered wild tubers and vegetables.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In many ways, the daily food of native South African families can be traced to the indigenous foods that their native African ancestors ate.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The Khoisan and Bantu traditionally ate roasted meat, and they also dried meat for later use.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The influence of their diet is reflected in the universal Southern African love of barbecue (generally called in South Africa by its Afrikaans name, a "braai") and biltong (dried preserved meat).
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The traditional beer was ubiquitous in the southern African diet, and the fermentation added additional nutrients to the diet.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] It was a traditional obligation for any family to be able to offer a visitor copious amounts of beer.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Beer brewing was done by women, and the status of a housewife in pre-colonial southern Africa depended significantly on her skill at brewing delicious beer.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Milk was historically one of the most important components of the southern African diet.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Cattle were considered a man's most important possession.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In order to marry, a man had to compensate his prospective in-laws with a gift of cattle as a dowry for his bride.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] A married man was expected to provide a generous supply of milk to his wife and children, along with meat whenever he slaughtered cattle, sheep or goats.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Because there was no refrigeration, milk was mostly soured into a kind of yogurt.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The young men of the family often took care of the cattle far away from the villages at "cattle posts," and they sent a steady stream of yogurt home on behalf of their fathers.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Today, many South Africans of African origin enjoy drinking sour milk products that are sold in the supermarket, comparable to American buttermilk, yogurt, and sour cream.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] On weekends they will have a "braai", and the meal usually consists of "pap and vleis", which is maize porridge and grilled meat as has historically been done in the region.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The basic ingredients include seafood, meat products (including wild game), poultry, as well as grains, fresh fruits and vegetables.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Fruits include apples, grapes, mangoes, bananas, papayas, avocado, oranges, peaches and apricots.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Desserts may simply be fruit, but there are some more western-style puddings, such as malva pudding, reminiscent of sticky toffee pudding, which was inspired by both British cuisine and Dutch cuisine.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Meat products include lamb, and game like venison, ostrich, and impala.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The seafood includes crayfish, prawns, tuna, mussels, oysters, calamari, mackerel, and lobster.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] There are also several types of traditional and modern alcoholic beverages including many European-style beers.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] A typical West African meal is made with starchy items and can contain meat, fish, as well as various spices and herbs.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] A wide array of staples are eaten across the region, including fufu, banku, kenkey (originating from Ghana), foutou, couscous, tô, and garri, which are served alongside soups and stews.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Fufu is often made from starchy root vegetables such as yams, cocoyams, or cassava, and also from cereal grains like millet, sorghum or plantains.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The staple grain or starch varies between regions and ethnic groups, although corn has gained significant ground as it is cheap, swells to greater volumes and creates a beautiful white final product that is greatly desired.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Banku and kenkey are maize dough staples, and garri is made from dried grated cassavas.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Rice dishes are also widely eaten in the region, especially in the dry Sahel belt inland.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Examples of these include the Senegalese dish thieboudienne also known as benachin or Jollof rice, a pan-West African rice dish similar to Arab kabsah.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Seeds of Guinea pepper (Aframomum melegueta, also called grains of paradise or melegueta pepper), a native West African plant, were used as a spice and even reached Europe, through North African middlemen, during the Middle Ages.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Centuries before the influence of the Europeans, West Africans were trading with the Arab world and spices like cinnamon, cloves, and mint were not unknown, therefore becoming part of the local flavorings.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Centuries later, the Portuguese, French and British influenced the regional cuisines, but only to a limited extent.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Cooking techniques include roasting, baking, boiling, frying, mashing, and spicing.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] A range of sweets and savories are also prepared.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Cooking techniques of West Africa are changing.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In the past West Africans ate much less meat and used native oils (palm oil on the coast and shea butter in Sahelian regions).
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Baobob leaf and numerous local greens were everyday staples during certain times of the year.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Today the diet is much heavier in meats, salt, and fats.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Many dishes combine fish and meat, including dried and fermented fish.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Flaked and dried fish is often fried in oil, and sometimes cooked in sauce made with hot peppers, onions, tomatoes, various spices (such as soumbala), and water to prepare a highly flavored stew.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] In some areas beef and mutton are preferred, and goat meat is the dominant red meat.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Suya, a popular grilled spicy meat kebab flavored with peanuts and other spices, is sold by street vendors as a snack or evening meal and is typically made with beef or chicken.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] It is common to have a preponderance of seafood, which as earlier stated, is sometimes also mixed with other meat products.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Guinea fowl and chicken eggs are also preferred.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] With regard to beverages, water has a very strong ritual significance in many West African nations (particularly in dry areas) and water is often the first thing an African host will offer their guest.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Palm wine is also a common beverage made from the fermented sap of various types of palm trees and is usually sold in sweet (less-fermented, retaining more of the sap's sugar) or sour (fermented longer, making it stronger and less sweet) varieties.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The exact origins of Bitter Leaf soup appear to be unknown thought it is known to have been prepared and eaten for hundreds of years.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The dish traditionally consists of fish, meat (usually beef), bitter leaves, palm oil, and an array of spices and seasonings.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Shellfish such as shrimp or crayfish are often used alongside fish in the preparation of Bitter Leaf Soup.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] Due to the bitterness of bitter leaf, the bitter leaf is washed thoroughly to diminish the bitterness before being cooked with the rest of the ingredients.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] It is widely consumed in West Africa, especially Nigeria where it is associated with the Igbo people and referred to as Ofe Onugbu.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The Bitter Leaf itself is known scientifically as Vernonia amygdalina and is native to Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:asida/african-cuisine] The bitter taste comes from the alkaloids contained within the plant.
[src:asida/agar] As found in nature, agar is a mixture of two components, the linear polysaccharide agarose and a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules called agaropectin.
[src:asida/agar] It forms the supporting structure in the cell walls of certain species of algae, and is released on boiling.
[src:asida/agar] The processing of food-grade agar removes the agaropectin, and the commercial product is essentially pure agarose.
[src:asida/agar] Agar has been used as an ingredient in desserts throughout Asia and also as a solid substrate to contain culture media for microbiological work.
[src:asida/agar] Agar can be used as a laxative; an appetite suppressant; a vegan substitute for gelatin; a thickener for soups; in fruit preserves, ice cream, and other desserts; as a clarifying agent in brewing; and for sizing paper and fabrics.
[src:asida/agar] The word *agar* comes from **agar-agar**, the Malay name for red algae (*Gigartina*, *Eucheuma*, *Gracilaria*) from which the jelly is produced.
[src:asida/agar] It is also known as **kanten** (Japanese: 寒天) (from the phrase ***kan**-zarashi tokoro**ten*** (寒晒し心太) or "cold-exposed agar"), **Japanese isinglass**, **China grass**, **Ceylon moss**, and **Jaffna moss**.
[src:asida/agar] *Gracilaria edulis* or its synonym *G. lichenoides* is specifically referred to as **agal-agal** or **Ceylon agar**.
[src:asida/agar] Macroalgae have been used widely as food by coastal cultures, especially in Southeast Asia.
[src:asida/agar] In the Philippines, *Gracilaria*, known as *gulaman* (also *guraman*, *gar-garao*, or *gulaman dagat*, among other names) in Tagalog, have been harvested and used as food for centuries, eaten both fresh or sun-dried and turned into jellies.
[src:asida/agar] Carrageenan, derived from gusô (*Eucheuma* spp.), which also congeals into a gel-like texture is also used similarly among the Visayan peoples and have been recorded in the even earlier *Diccionario De La Lengua Bisaya, Hiligueina y Haraia de la isla de Panay y Sugbu y para las demas islas* (c.
[src:asida/agar] 1637) of the Augustinian missionary Alonso de Méntrida (in Spanish).
[src:asida/agar] In the book, Méntrida describes gusô as being cooked until it melts, and then allowed to congeal into a sour dish.
[src:asida/agar] In Ambon Island in the Maluku Islands of Indonesia, agar is extracted from *Graciliaria* and eaten as a type of pickle or a sauce.
[src:asida/agar] Jelly seaweeds were also favoured and foraged by Malay communities living on the coasts of the Riau Archipelago and Singapore in Southeast Asia for centuries.
[src:asida/agar] 19th century records indicate that dried *Graciliaria* were one of the bulk exports of British Malaya to China.
[src:asida/agar] Poultices made from agar were also used for swollen knee joints and sores in Johore and Singapore.
[src:asida/agar] Agar normally solidifies at room temperature without the need to freeze.
[src:asida/agar] Agar was first subjected to chemical analysis in 1859 by the French chemist Anselme Payen, who had obtained agar from the marine algae *Gelidium corneum*.
[src:asida/agar] Beginning in the late 19th century, agar began to be used as a solid medium for growing various microbes.
[src:asida/agar] Agar was first described for use in microbiology in 1882 by the German microbiologist Walther Hesse, an assistant working in Robert Koch's laboratory, on the suggestion of his wife Fanny Hesse.
[src:asida/agar] Agar quickly supplanted gelatin as the base of microbiological media, due to its higher melting temperature, allowing microbes to be grown at higher temperatures without the media liquefying.
[src:asida/agar] With its newfound use in microbiology, agar production quickly increased.
[src:asida/agar] This production centered on Japan, which produced most of the world's agar until World War II.
[src:asida/agar] However, with the outbreak of World War II, many nations were forced to establish domestic agar industries in order to continue microbiological research.
[src:asida/agar] Around the time of World War II, approximately 2,500 tons of agar were produced annually.
[src:asida/agar] By the mid-1970s, production worldwide had increased dramatically to approximately 10,000 tons each year.
[src:asida/agar] Since then, production of agar has fluctuated due to unstable and sometimes over-utilized seaweed populations.
[src:asida/agar] Agar consists of a mixture of two polysaccharides: agarose and agaropectin.
[src:asida/agar] Agarose constitutes about 70% of the mixture, while agaropectin constitutes about 30% of it.
[src:asida/agar] Agarose is a linear polymer made up of repeating units of agarobiose, a disaccharide made up of D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-L-galactopyranose.
[src:asida/agar] Agaropectin is a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules that occur in lesser amounts, and is made up of alternating units of D-galactose and L-galactose heavily modified with acidic side-groups, such as sulfate, glucuronate, and pyruvate.
[src:asida/agar] Agar exhibits a phenomenon known as hysteresis whereby, when mixed with water, it solidifies and forms a gel below about 32–42 °C (305–315 K; 90–108 °F), which is called the gel point, and melts above 85 °C (358 K; 185 °F), which is the melting point.
[src:asida/agar] Hysteresis is the property of having a difference between the gel point and melting point temperatures.
[src:asida/agar] This property lends a suitable balance between easy melting and good gel stability at relatively high temperatures.
[src:asida/agar] Since many scientific applications require incubation at temperatures close to human body temperature (37 °C), agar is more appropriate than other solidifying agents that melt at this temperature, such as gelatin.
[src:asida/agar] Agar-agar is a natural vegetable gelatin counterpart.
[src:asida/agar] It is white and semi-translucent when sold in packages as washed and dried strips or in powdered form.
[src:asida/agar] It can be used to make jellies, puddings, and custards.
[src:asida/agar] When making jelly, it is boiled in water until the solids dissolve.
[src:asida/agar] Sweetener, flavoring, coloring, fruits and or vegetables are then added, and the liquid is poured into molds to be served as desserts and vegetable aspics or incorporated with other desserts such as a layer of jelly in a cake.
[src:asida/agar] Agar-agar is approximately 80% dietary fiber, so it can serve as an intestinal regulator.
[src:asida/agar] Its bulking quality has been behind fad diets in Asia, for example the *kanten* (the Japanese word for agar-agar) diet.
[src:asida/agar] Once ingested, *kanten* triples in size and absorbs water.
[src:asida/agar] This results in the consumers feeling fuller.
[src:asida/agar] One use of agar in Japanese cuisine is in *anmitsu*, a dessert made of small cubes of agar jelly and served in a bowl with various fruits or other ingredients.
[src:asida/agar] It is also the main ingredient in *mizu yōkan*, another popular Japanese food.
[src:asida/agar] In Philippine cuisine, it is used to make the jelly bars in the various gulaman refreshments like *sago't gulaman*, *samalamig*, or desserts such as *buko pandan*, *agar flan*, *halo-halo*, *fruit cocktail jelly*, and the black and red *gulaman* used in various fruit salads.
[src:asida/agar] In Vietnamese cuisine, jellies made of flavored layers of agar-agar, called *thạch*, are a popular dessert, and are often made in ornate molds for special occasions.
[src:asida/agar] In Indian cuisine, agar is used for making desserts.
[src:asida/agar] In Burmese cuisine, a sweet jelly known as *kyauk kyaw* is made from agar.
[src:asida/agar] Agar jelly is widely used in Taiwanese bubble tea.
[src:asida/agar] It can be used as addition to (or as a replacement for) pectin in jelly, jam, or marmalade, as a substitute to gelatin for its superior gelling properties, and as a strengthening ingredient in souffles and custards.
[src:asida/agar] Another use of agar-agar is in a Russian dish *ptich'ye moloko* (bird's milk), a rich jellified custard (or soft meringue) used as a cake filling or chocolate-glazed as individual sweets.
[src:asida/agar] Agar-agar may also be used as the gelling agent in gel clarification, a culinary technique used to clarify stocks, sauces, and other liquids.
[src:asida/agar] Mexico has traditional candies made out of Agar gelatin, most of them in colorful, half-circle shapes that resemble a melon or watermelon fruit slice, and commonly covered with sugar.
[src:asida/agar] Agar-agar is an allowed nonorganic/nonsynthetic additive used as a thickener, gelling agent, texturizer, moisturizer, emulsifier, flavor enhancer, and absorbent in certified organic foods.
[src:asida/agar] An agar plate or Petri dish is used to provide a growth medium using a mix of agar and other nutrients in which microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, can be cultured and observed under the microscope.
[src:asida/agar] Agar is indigestible for many organisms so that microbial growth does not affect the gel used and it remains stable.
[src:asida/agar] Agar is typically sold commercially as a powder that can be mixed with water and prepared similarly to gelatin before use as a growth medium.
[src:asida/agar] Nutrients are typically added to meet the nutritional needs of the microbes organism, the formulations of which may be "undefined" where the precise composition is unknown, or "defined" where the exact chemical composition is known.
[src:asida/agar] Agar is often dispensed using a sterile media dispenser.
[src:asida/agar] Different algae produce various types of agar.
[src:asida/agar] Each agar has unique properties that suit different purposes.
[src:asida/agar] Because of the agarose component, the agar solidifies.
[src:asida/agar] When heated, agarose has the potential to melt and then solidify.
[src:asida/agar] Because of this property, they are referred to as "physical gels".
[src:asida/agar] In contrast, polyacrylamide polymerization is an irreversible process, and the resulting products are known as chemical gels.
[src:asida/agar] There are a variety of different types of agar that support the growth of different microorganisms.
[src:asida/agar] A nutrient agar may be permissive, allowing for the cultivation of any non-fastidious microorganisms; a commonly used nutrient agar for bacteria is the Luria Bertani (LB) agar which contains lysogeny broth, a nutrient-rich medium used for bacterial growth.
[src:asida/agar] Additionally, 2216 Marine Broth (MB) agar, with high salt content, is optimized for growing heterotrophic marine bacteria like those of the *Vibrio* genus, while Terrific Broth (TB) agar is used to non-selectively culture high yields of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:asida/agar] More generally, enriched media is an agar variety that is infused with the necessary nutrients required by fastidious organisms to grow.
[src:asida/agar] Despite the large diversity of agar mediums, yeast extract is a common ingredient across all varieties as it is a macronutrient that provides a nitrogen source for all bacterial cell types.
[src:asida/agar] Other fastidious organisms may require the addition of different biological fluids such as horse or sheep blood, serum, egg yolk, and so on.
[src:asida/agar] Agar plates can also be selective, and can be used to promote the growth of bacteria of interest while inhibiting others.
[src:asida/agar] A variety of chemicals may be added to create an environment favourable for specific types of bacteria or bacteria with certain properties, but not conducive for growth of others.
[src:asida/agar] For example, antibiotics may be added in cloning experiments whereby bacteria with antibiotic-resistant plasmid are selected.
[src:asida/agar] In addition to antibiotic treated agar, other selective and indicator agar plates include TCBS agar and MacConkey agar.
[src:asida/agar] Thiosulfate citrate bile salts sucrose (TCBS) agar is used to differentiate Vibrio species based on their sucrose metabolism, since only some will metabolize the sucrose in the plate and change its pH.
[src:asida/agar] Indicator dyes included in the gel will display a visual change of the pH by changing the gel color from green to yellow.
[src:asida/agar] MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet to selectively grow gram-negative bacteria and differentiate between species using pH-indicator dyes that demonstrate lactose metabolism properties.
[src:asida/agar] As a gel, an agar or agarose medium is porous and therefore can be used to measure microorganism motility and mobility.
[src:asida/agar] The gel's porosity is directly related to the concentration of agarose in the medium, so various levels of effective viscosity (from the cell's "point of view") can be selected, depending on the experimental objectives.
[src:asida/agar] A common identification assay involves culturing a sample of the organism deep within a block of nutrient agar.
[src:asida/agar] Cells will attempt to grow within the gel structure.
[src:asida/agar] Motile species will be able to migrate, albeit slowly, throughout the gel, and infiltration rates can then be visualized, whereas non-motile species will show growth only along the now-empty path introduced by the invasive initial sample deposition.
[src:asida/agar] Another setup commonly used for measuring chemotaxis and chemokinesis utilizes the under-agarose cell migration assay, whereby a layer of agarose gel is placed between a cell population and a chemoattractant.
[src:asida/agar] As a concentration gradient develops from the diffusion of the chemoattractant into the gel, various cell populations requiring different stimulation levels to migrate can then be visualized over time using microphotography as they tunnel upward through the gel against gravity along the gradient.
[src:asida/agar] Research grade agar is used extensively in plant biology as it is optionally supplemented with a nutrient and/or vitamin mixture that allows for seedling germination in Petri dishes under sterile conditions (given that the seeds are sterilized as well).
[src:asida/agar] Nutrient and/or vitamin supplementation for *Arabidopsis thaliana* is standard across most experimental conditions.
[src:asida/agar] Murashige & Skoog (MS) nutrient mix and Gamborg's B5 vitamin mix in general are used.
[src:asida/agar] A 1.0% agar/0.44% MS+vitamin dH2O solution is suitable for growth media between normal growth temps.
[src:asida/agar] When using agar, within any growth medium, it is important to know that the solidification of the agar is pH-dependent.
[src:asida/agar] The optimal range for solidification is between 5.4 and 5.7.
[src:asida/agar] Usually, the application of potassium hydroxide is needed to increase the pH to this range.
[src:asida/agar] A general guideline is about 600 μl 0.1M KOH per 250 ml GM.
[src:asida/agar] This entire mixture can be sterilized using the liquid cycle of an autoclave.
[src:asida/agar] This hormone/GM solution can be spread across the surface of Petri dishes sown with germinated and/or etiolated seedlings.
[src:asida/agar] Experiments with the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, however, have shown that choice of the gelling agent – agar or Gelrite – does influence phytohormone sensitivity of the plant cell culture.
[src:asida/agar] Gelidium agar is used primarily for bacteriological plates.
[src:asida/agar] Gracilaria agar is used mainly in food applications.
[src:asida/agar] In 2016, AMAM, a Japanese company, developed a prototype for agar-based commercial packaging system called Agar Plasticity, intended as a replacement for oil-based plastic packaging.
[src:asida/akika] According to hadith and the majority of Islamic scholars, two goats are sacrificed for a boy and one for a girl.
[src:asida/akika] If one cannot perform the slaughter on the seventh day, it may be done on the fourteenth or the twenty-first day.
[src:asida/akika] If one is still unable to do so, it may be performed at any time before the child reaches puberty.
[src:asida/akika] The aqiqah is sunnah and mustahabb; it is not obligatory, so there is no sin upon one who does not perform it.
[src:asida/akika] According to a hadith in Muwatta Imam Malik, Fatima donated, in silver equivalent, the weight of the shaved hair of her children Hasan, Husayn, Umm Kulthum, and Zaynab.
[src:asida/akika] Ja'far al-Sadiq, a great grandchild of the Islamic prophet Muhammad and a prominent scholar in his era, claimed that the shaving, slaughtering for aqiqah, and naming of the child should, ideally, be done within one hour.
[src:asida/akika] According to another hadith from Ja'far al-Sadiq, every born is in pawn of aqiqah; namely, it would be exposed to death/kinds of calamities if they don't do aqiqah for the child.
[src:asida/akika] It is Sunnah for the parents to eat from the meat of aqiqah.
[src:asida/akika] Abu Talib ibn Abd al-Muttalib performed aqiqah for Muhammad on the seventh day of his birth and invited members of his family for the occasion, who asked "what is this?" to which he replied "aqiqah for Ahmad".
[src:asida/akika] He claimed to have named him Ahmad "because of the praises of the inhabitants of the skies and the Earth for him".
[src:asida/akika] Muhammad is said to have performed aqiqah for both Hasan ibn Ali and Husayn ibn Ali, his grandsons, on the seventh day of their births respectively by sacrificing one sheep each; the leg of which was given to the nurse that helped with the delivery.
[src:asida/akika] Anointing the baby with the blood of the sacrificed animal for aqiqah was a common practice among Arab pagans and was, therefore, prohibited in Islam.
[src:asida/akika] The Shafiʿi madhdhab allows for an aqiqah practice after the death of a child.
[src:asida/akika] This is also the school of law that emphasizes the child’s potential for shafaʿa (intercession).
[src:asida/akika] Two prominent representatives of the Shafiʿi madhhab who defend this idea of a deceased child as a heavenly intercessor are alSuyuti (ca.
[src:asida/akika] Abu Hanifa, unlike other jurists, held that the aqiqah sacrifice was an illegitimate practice from the pre-Islamic pagan period in Arabia.
[src:asida/akika] The tradition of animal sacrifice and weighing the first haircut against gold or silver for charity appear to have their origins in pre-Islamic Arabia.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] As a political domain, it successively constituted a province of the Umayyad Caliphate, initiated by the Caliph al-Walid I (711–750); the Emirate of Córdoba (c.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Under the Caliphate of Córdoba, the city of Córdoba became one of the leading cultural and economic centres throughout the Mediterranean Basin, Europe, and the Islamic world.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Achievements that advanced Islamic and Western science came from al-Andalus, including major advances in trigonometry (Jabir ibn Aflah), astronomy (al-Zarqali), surgery (al-Zahrawi), pharmacology (Ibn Zuhr), and agronomy (Ibn Bassal and Abu'l-Khayr al-Ishbili).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Al-Andalus became a conduit for cultural and scientific exchange between the Islamic and Christian worlds.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] For much of its history, al-Andalus existed in conflict with Christian kingdoms to the north.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] After the fall of the Umayyad Caliphate of Cordoba by 1031, al-Andalus was fragmented into *taifa* states and principalities, some of which (such as the Taifa of Toledo, the Taifa of Zaragoza, the Taifa of Seville and the Taifa of Badajoz) reached considerable territorial extent.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] After the Christian capture of Toledo in 1085, the Almoravid empire intervened and repelled attacks on the region, then brought al-Andalus under direct Almoravid rule.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] For the next century and a half, al-Andalus became a province of the Muslim empires of the Almoravids and their successors, the Almohads, both based in Marrakesh.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Ultimately, the northern Christian kingdoms overpowered the Muslim states to the south.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In the 13th century, most of the south quickly fell under Christian rule, with Gharb al-Andalus, the Guadalquivir Valley and Eastern al-Andalus falling to Portuguese, Castilian, and Aragonese conquests.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] This left the Emirate of Granada as the remaining Muslim state on the Iberian Peninsula, which became a tributary state of the Crown of Castile, before surrendering in 1492 to the Catholic Monarchs.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The toponym *al-Andalus* is first attested by inscriptions on coins minted in 716 by the new Muslim government of Iberia.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] These coins, called *dinars*, were inscribed in both Latin and Arabic.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The etymology of the name *al-Andalus* has traditionally been derived from the name of the Vandals (*vándalos* in Spanish, *vândalos* in Portuguese).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Since the 1980s, several alternative etymologies have challenged this tradition.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 1986, Joaquín Vallvé proposed that *al-Andalus* was a corruption of the name *Atlantis*.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Heinz Halm in 1989 derived the name from a Gothic term, **landahlauts*, and in 2002, Georg Bossong suggested its derivation from a pre-Roman substrate.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] During the caliphate of the Umayyad Caliph Al-Walid I, the commander Tariq ibn-Ziyad led an army of 7,000 that landed at Gibraltar on April 30, 711, ostensibly to intervene in a Visigothic civil war.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] After a decisive victory over King Roderic at the Battle of Guadalete on 19 July 711, Tariq, accompanied by his *mawla*, governor Musa ibn Nusayr of Ifriqiya, brought most of the Visigothic Kingdom under Muslim rule in a seven-year campaign.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] They crossed the Pyrenees and occupied Visigothic Septimania in southern France.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Most of the Iberian peninsula became part of the expanding Umayyad Empire, under the name of *al-Andalus*.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] It was organised as a province subordinate to Ifriqiya, so, for the first few decades, the governors of al-Andalus were appointed by the emir of Kairouan, rather than the Caliph in Damascus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The regional capital was set at Córdoba, and the first influx of Muslim settlers was widely distributed.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Following the Muslim conquest of Spain, al-Andalus, then at its greatest extent, was divided into five administrative units, corresponding very roughly to: modern Andalusia; Castile and León; Navarre, Aragon, and Catalonia; Portugal and Galicia; and the Languedoc-Roussillon area of Occitania.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The small army Tariq led in the initial conquest consisted mostly of Berbers, while Musa's largely Arab force of over 12,000 soldiers was accompanied by a group of *mawālī* (Arabic, موالي), that is, non-Arab Muslims, who were clients of the Arabs.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Berber soldiers accompanying Tariq were garrisoned in the centre and the north of the peninsula, as well as in the Pyrenees, while the Berber colonists who followed settled in all parts of the country – north, east, south and west.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Visigothic lords who agreed to recognise Muslim suzerainty were allowed to retain their fiefs (notably, in Murcia, Galicia, and the Ebro valley).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Resistant Visigoths took refuge in the Cantabrian highlands, where they carved out a rump state, the Kingdom of Asturias.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In the 720s, the al-Andalus governors launched several *sa'ifa* raids into Aquitaine but were decisively defeated by Duke Odo the Great of Aquitaine at the Battle of Toulouse (721).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] At the Battle of Poitiers in 732, the al-Andalus raiding army was defeated by Charles Martel and Al Ghafiqi was killed.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 734, the Andalusi launched raids to the east, capturing Avignon and Arles, and overran much of Provence.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 737, they travelled up the Rhône valley, reaching as far north as Burgundy.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Charles Martel of the Franks, with the assistance of Liutprand of the Lombards, invaded Burgundy and Provence and expelled the raiders by 739.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 740, a Berber Revolt erupted in the Maghreb (North Africa).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] To put down the rebellion, the Umayyad Caliph Hisham dispatched a large Arab army, composed of regiments (*Junds*) from Bilad Ash-Sham, to North Africa.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] This Umayyad army was defeated by the Berber rebels at the Battle of Bagdoura (in Morocco).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Heartened by the victories of their North African brethren, the Berbers of al-Andalus quickly raised their own revolt.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Berber garrisons in the north of the Iberian Peninsula mutinied, deposed their Arab commanders, and organised a large rebel army to march against the strongholds of Toledo, Córdoba, and Algeciras.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 741, Balj bin Bishr led a detachment of some 10,000 Arab troops across the straits.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Arab governor of al-Andalus, joined by this force, was victorious over the Berber rebels in a series of battles in 742.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] A dispute erupted between the Syrian commanders and the Andalusi, the so-called "original Arabs" of the earlier contingents.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Syrians defeated them at the hard-fought Battle of Aqua Portora in August 742 but were too few to impose themselves on the province.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Egypt jund was divided between Beja (Alentejo) in the west and Tudmir (Murcia) in the east.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The arrival of the Syrians substantially increased the Arab element in the Iberian peninsula and helped strengthen the Muslim hold on the south.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] However, at the same time, unwilling to be governed, the Syrian *junds* carried on an existence of autonomous feudal anarchy, severely destabilising the authority of the governor of al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] A second significant consequence of the revolt was the expansion of the Kingdom of the Asturias, hitherto confined to enclaves in the Cantabrian highlands.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] After the rebellious Berber garrisons evacuated the northern frontier fortresses, the Christian king Alfonso I of Asturias set about immediately seizing the empty forts for himself, quickly adding the northwestern provinces of Galicia and León to his fledgling kingdom.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Asturians evacuated the Christian populations from the towns and villages of the Galician-Leonese lowlands, creating an empty buffer zone in the Douro River valley (the "Desert of the Duero").
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] This newly emptied frontier remained roughly in place for the next few centuries as the boundary between the Christian north and the Islamic south.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] On the Muslim side of the frontier, al-Andalus had three large march territories (*thaghr*, pl.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] These disturbances and disorder also allowed the Franks, now under the leadership of Pepin the Short, to invade the strategic strip of Septimania in 752, hoping to deprive al-Andalus of an easy launching pad for raids into Francia.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] After a lengthy siege, the last Arab stronghold, the citadel of Narbonne, finally fell to the Franks in 759.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Al-Andalus was sealed off at the Pyrenees.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The third consequence of the Berber revolt was the collapse of the authority of the Damascus Caliphate over the western provinces.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] With the Umayyad Caliphs distracted by the challenge of the Abbasids in the east, the western provinces of the Maghreb and al-Andalus spun out of their control.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] From around 745, the Fihrids, an illustrious local Arab clan descended from Oqba ibn Nafi al-Fihri, seized power in the western provinces and ruled them almost as a private family empire of their own – Abd al-Rahman ibn Habib al-Fihri in Ifriqiya and Yūsuf al-Fihri in al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Fihrids welcomed the fall of the Umayyads in the east, in 750, and sought to reach an understanding with the Abbasids, hoping they might be allowed to continue their autonomous existence.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] But when the Abbasids rejected the offer and demanded submission, the Fihrids declared independence and, probably out of spite, invited the deposed remnants of the Umayyad clan to take refuge in their dominions.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] It was a fateful decision that they soon regretted, for the Umayyads, the sons and grandsons of caliphs, had a more legitimate claim to rule than the Fihrids themselves.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Rebellious-minded local lords, disenchanted with the autocratic rule of the Fihrids, conspired with the arriving Umayyad exiles.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 755, the exiled Umayyad prince Abd al-Rahman I (also called *al-Dākhil*, the 'Immigrant') arrived on the coast of Spain.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] He had fled the Abbasids, who had overthrown the Umayyads in Damascus and were slaughtering members of that family, and then he spent four years in exile in North Africa, assessing the political situation in al-Andalus across the Straits of Gibraltar, before he landed at Almuñécar.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] News of his arrival spread across al-Andalus, and when word reached its governor, Yūsuf al-Fihri, he was not pleased.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] During this time, Abd al-Rahman and his supporters quickly conquered Málaga and then Seville, finally besieging the capital of al-Andalus, Córdoba.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Abd al-Rahman's army was exhausted after their conquest, meanwhile Governor Yūsuf al-Fihri had returned from quashing another rebellion with his army.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The siege of Córdoba began, and noticing the starving state of Abd al-Rahman's army, al-Fihri began throwing lavish feasts every day as the siege went on, to tempt Abd al Rahman's supporters to defect to his side.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] However, Abd al-Rahman persisted, even rejecting a truce that would have allowed Abd al-Rahman to marry al-Fihri's daughter.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] After decisively defeating Yūsuf al-Fihri's army, Abd al-Rahman was able to conquer Córdoba, where he proclaimed himself emir in 756.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The rest of al-Andalus was easily conquered, and Abd al-Rahman soon had control of all of al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] By far the most important of these invasions was the attempted reconquest by the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 763 Caliph Al-Mansur of the Abbasids installed al-Ala ibn-Mugith as governor of Africa (whose title gave him dominion over the province of al-Andalus).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] He planned to invade and destroy the Emirate of Córdoba, so in response Abd al Rahman fortified himself within the fortress of Carmona with a tenth as many soldiers as al-Ala ibn-Mugith.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] After a long siege, it appeared that Abd al Rahman would be defeated, but in a last stand Abd al Rahman with his outnumbered forces opened the gates of the fortress and charged at the resting Abbasid army, and decisively defeated them.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Abd al Rahman I died in 788 after a lengthy and prosperous reign.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] He was succeeded by his son, Hisham I, who secured power by exiling his brother who had tried to rebel against him.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Hisham enjoyed a stable reign of eight years and was succeeded by his son Al-Hakam I.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The next few decades were relatively uneventful, with only occasional minor rebellions, and saw the rise of the emirate.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 822 Al Hakam died and was succeeded by Abd al-Rahman II, the first great emir of Córdoba.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] He rose to power with no opposition and sought to reform the emirate.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] He quickly reorganised the bureaucracy to be more efficient and built many mosques across the emirate.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] During his reign science and art flourished, as many scholars fled the Abbasid caliphate due to the disastrous Fourth Fitna.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The scholar Abbas ibn Firnas made an attempt to fly, though accounts vary on his success.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 852 Abd al Rahman II died, leaving behind him a powerful and well-established state that had become one of the most powerful in the Mediterranean.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Abd al Rahman was succeeded by Muhammad I of Córdoba, who according to legend had to wear women's clothing to sneak into the imperial palace and be crowned, since he was not the heir apparent.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] His reign marked a decline in the emirate, which was ended by Abd al-Rahman III.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] His reign was marked by multiple rebellions, which were dealt with poorly and weakened the emirate, most disastrously following the rebellion of Umar ibn Hafsun.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] When Muhammad died, he was succeeded by emir Abdullah ibn Muhammad al-Umawi whose power barely reached outside of the city of Córdoba.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] As Ibn Hafsun ravaged the south, Abdullah did almost nothing, and slowly became more and more isolated, barely speaking to anyone.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Abdullah purged his administration of his brothers, which lessened the bureaucracy's loyalty towards him.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Around this time several local Arab lords began to revolt, including one Kurayb ibn Khaldun, who was able to conquer Seville.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Some loyalists tried to quell the rebellion, but without proper material support, their efforts were in vain.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] He declared that the next emir would be his grandson Abd al-Rahman III, ignoring the claims of his four living children.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Abdullah died in 912, and the throne passed to Abd al Rahman III.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Through force of arms and diplomacy, he put down the rebellions that had disrupted his grandfather's reign, obliterating Ibn Hafsun and hunting down his sons.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] After this he led several sieges against the Christians, sacking the city of Pamplona, and restoring some prestige to the emirate.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Meanwhile, across the sea the Fatimids had risen up in force, ousted the Abbasid government in North Africa, and declared themselves a caliphate.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Inspired by this action, Abd al Rahman joined the rebellion and declared himself caliph in 929.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] For nearly 100 years under the Córdoban Umayyad period, from the 9th century to the 10th, al-Andalus also extended its presence from Fraxinetum into the Alps with a series of organised raids.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The period of the Caliphate is seen as the golden age of al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Córdoba under the Caliphate, with a population of more than half a million, eventually overtook Constantinople as the largest and most prosperous city in the world.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Al-Andalus became a centre for the arts, medicine, science, music, literature and philosophy.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The work of its most important philosophers and scientists, such as Abulcasis and Averroes, had a major influence on the intellectual life of medieval Europe.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Muslims and non-Muslims often came from abroad to study at the libraries and universities of al-Andalus, and after the reconquest of Toledo, several translation institutions such as the Toledo School of Translators were established for translating books and texts from Arabic into Latin.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The most noted figures in this being Gerard of Cremona and Michael Scot, who took these works to Italy.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The transmission of ideas significantly affected the formation of the European Renaissance.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Caliphate of Córdoba also had extensive trade with other parts of the Mediterranean, including Christian parts.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Trade goods included luxury items (silk, ceramics, gold), essential foodstuffs (grain, olive oil, wine), and containers (such as ceramics for storing perishables).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In the tenth century, Amalfitans were already trading Fatimid and Byzantine silks in Córdoba.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Later references to Amalfitan merchants were sometimes used to emphasise the previous golden age of Córdoba.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Fatimid Egypt was a supplier of many luxury goods, including elephant tusks, and raw or carved crystals.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Fatimids were traditionally thought to be the only supplier of such goods, and control over these trade routes would be a cause for conflict between the Umayyads and Fatimids.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Caliphate of Córdoba effectively collapsed during a ruinous civil war between 1009 and 1013, although it was not finally abolished until 1031 when *al-Andalus* broke up into a number of mostly independent mini-states and principalities called *taifas*.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 1013, invading Berbers sacked Córdoba, massacring its inhabitants, pillaging the city, and burning the palace complex to the ground.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The largest of the taifas to emerge were Badajoz (*Batalyaws*), Toledo (*Ṭulayṭulah*), Zaragoza (*Saraqusta*), and Granada (*Ġarnāṭah*).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] During the eleventh century several centres of power existed among the taifas, and the political situation shifted rapidly.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The taifas were vulnerable and divided but had immense wealth.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] During its prominence the Taifa of Seville produced technically complex lusterware and exerted significant influence on ceramic production across al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In the 1080s, the *taifa* kingdoms began to face an existential threat from the Christian kingdoms to the north, as Alfonso VI of Castile escalated attacks against them.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 1083, he led a punitive expedition against Seville that reached all the way to Tarifa at the southern tip of al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 1085, he annexed Toledo, a turning point which galvanised the remaining *taifa* leaders into seeking outside help.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] After the fall of Toledo, most of the major *taifa* rulers agreed to request the intervention of the Almoravids, a Berber empire based in Marrakesh that had conquered much of northwest Africa.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Almoravid leader, Yusuf Ibn Tashfin, led several campaigns into al-Andalus, initially in defence of the *taifa* kingdoms.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] At the Battle of Sagrajas (or Battle of Zallaqa in Arabic), a Muslim army led by the Almoravids soundly defeated Alfonso VI.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] By 1090, however, Yusuf ibn Tashfin was disillusioned with the disunity of the *taifa* leaders and he returned on a campaign to conquer al-Andalus instead.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Most of the *taifas*, except for Zaragoza, were annexed by 1094.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Valencia, which had come under the control of El Cid at the end of its taifa period, was eventually occupied in 1102, after El Cid's death.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The rise and fall of the Almoravids is sometimes seen as an expression of Ibn Khaldun's asabiyyah paradigm.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] By 1147, the Almoravids were overthrown in North Africa by the Almohads, another Berber dynasty, under the leadership of Abd al-Mu'min.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] As Almoravid rule collapsed, another brief period of *taifa* kingdoms followed in al-Andalus, during which the Christian kingdoms expanded southward again.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] From 1146 onward, the Almohads intervened and took control of al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] One of Abd al-Mu'min's successors, Ya'qub al-Mansur, won a major victory over the Castilian Alfonso VIII at the Battle of Alarcos in 1195.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 1212, a coalition of Christian kings under the leadership of Alfonso VIII defeated the Almohads at the Battle of Las Navas de Tolosa.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Almohad rule was diminished in prestige and in 1228 the Almohad caliph al-Ma'mun withdrew from al-Andalus altogether.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In this political vacuum, a new wave of *taifa* kingdoms emerged, which were progressively conquered by Portugal, Castile, and Aragon.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Córdoba was conquered in 1236 and Seville was conquered in 1248.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Some Muslim city-states, such as Murcia and Niebla, survived as vassal kingdoms of Castile until the 1260s.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Only the region of Granada remained unconquered.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] From the mid 13th to the late 15th century, the only remaining domain of al-Andalus was the Emirate of Granada, the last Muslim stronghold in the Iberian Peninsula.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The emirate was established by Muhammad ibn al-Ahmar in 1230 and was ruled by the Nasrid dynasty, the longest reigning dynasty in the history of al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Although surrounded by Castilian lands, the emirate was wealthy through being tightly integrated in Mediterranean trade networks and enjoyed a period of considerable cultural and economic prosperity.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Despite internal conflicts, the Nasrids of Granada were able to survive in part by playing the Christian kingdoms of the north against each other, while at other times soliciting aid from the Marinids, a new Berber dynasty ruling in North Africa from their capital in Fez.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] For much of its existence, Granada paid tribute to the Castilian kings.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Along with this political status, its favourable geographic location, with the Sierra Nevada as a natural barrier, helped to prolong Nasrid rule.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Granada also accommodated a large number of Muslim refugees fleeing the *Reconquista* or expelled from Christian-controlled territories, which grew the city and the emirate's population.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The city even became one of the largest in Europe throughout the 15th century in terms of population.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The most visible legacy of the Nasrids is the Alhambra, their fortified palace complex, partly preserved today.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The independent Nasrid kingdom was also a trade hub between the Atlantic and Mediterranean, and was frequented especially by Genoese merchants.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Marinids intervened in the south of the Iberian Peninsula multiple times up until their defeat at the Battle of Río Salado in 1340.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] After this, they ceased to play a major role.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The subsequent internal turmoil within Castile, however, helped Nasrid Granada to enjoy a period of relative external peace and internal prosperity until the end of the 14th century, under the reigns of Yusuf I (r.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Important cultural figures, such as Ibn al-Khatib, Ibn Zamrak, and Ibn Khaldun all served in the Nasrid court during this period.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 1468, Isabella, the only child of Henry IV of Castile, married Ferdinand, the son of John II of Aragon, and by 1479 they were rulers of a united Castile and Aragon.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] This development meant that Granada could no longer exploit divisions between the two kingdoms and the new royal couple, also known as the Catholic Monarchs, were united in their intention to conquer it.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The final war to conquer Granada began in earnest in 1482.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Year by year, the Christian advance captured new cities and fortresses until the last Nasrid ruler, Muhammad XI (known as Boabdil to the Christians), formally surrendered Granada to the Catholic Monarchs on January 2, 1492.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] By this time Muslims in Castile numbered half a million.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] After the fall, "100,000 had died or been enslaved, 200,000 emigrated, and 200,000 remained as the residual population.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] From 1492 to 1493, tens of thousands of expulsed Muslims and Jews from al-Andalus were rescued when the Ottomans under orders of Sultan Bayezid II sent ships.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Thousands of Jews were transported to Ottoman lands, and many settled in North Africa.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Mass forced conversions of Muslims in 1499 led to a revolt that spread to Alpujarras and the mountains of Ronda; after this uprising the capitulations were revoked.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In 1502 the Catholic Monarchs decreed the forced conversion of all Muslims living under the rule of the Crown of Castile, although in the kingdoms of Aragon and Valencia (both now part of Spain) the open practice of Islam was allowed until 1526.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Descendants of the Muslims were subject to expulsions from Spain between 1609 and 1614 (see Expulsion of the Moriscos).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The last mass prosecution against Moriscos for crypto-Islamic practices occurred in Granada in 1727, with most of those convicted receiving relatively light sentences.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Morisco community including these final convicts kept their identity alive at least through the late eighteenth century.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] There was much scientific activity in al-Andalus, especially in the fields of medicine, astronomy, mathematics, and agronomy.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] At the same time, Andalusi scholars were also highly active in philosophy (see below), especially in the field of logic.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The earliest evidence of such activities in al-Andalus dates to the reign of Abd ar-Rahman II (r.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] 822–852), when developments were spurred by exposure to older works translated from, Greek, Persian and other languages.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Scientific studies continued to be pursued in the following centuries, though certain fields and subjects thrived more depending on the period.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Scholars often worked in many different and overlapping subjects, so it is difficult to place those discussed here into a single scientific field each.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] There were many notable surgeons, physicians, and medical scholars from al-Andalus including Ibn al-Baytar (d.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] 1248), Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi (Albucasis; d.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] 1360), Abu Marwan 'Abd al-Malik ibn Habib (d.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] 853), and Abu Marwan ibn Zuhr (Avenzoar; d.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] This encyclopaedia is also significant for its inclusion of al-Zahrawi's personal experiences as a surgeon, which provided important case studies for aspiring surgeons.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] This distinguishes it from other strictly factual medical works of the time, most notably Ibn Sina's *Canon of Medicine*.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Ibn Habib's work is significant because it is one of the oldest known writings in the field of prophetic medicine, which uses hadiths to create Islamic-based medicinal guidelines.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] His book is also significant because it uses principles of Galenic medicine, such as humorism and the theory of four temperaments, as the basis of its medical recommendations.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The ibn Zuhr family played a very important role in the production of Andalusi medical knowledge, as they produced five generations of medical experts, particularly in the fields of dietary sciences and medicaments.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In *Kitab al-Taysir* he provides one of the earliest clinical descriptions of the scabies mite.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The Maristan of Granada was founded in 1367 by the Nasrid ruler Muhammad V of Granada and stands as one of the clearest examples of institutional medicine in late al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Established as a charitable hospital in the Islamic tradition, it provided care for the sick, including those suffering from mental illness, and was funded through religious endowment.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Contemporary sources describe it as a purpose-built structure organised around a central courtyard with water features, reflecting both hygienic and therapeutic concerns.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The maristan illustrates the integration of medical practice, urban planning, and social welfare in Nasrid Granada, continuing the broader Andalusi engagement with the classical medical heritage of figures such as Ibn Sina while adapting it to local needs.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The maristam has reopened in recent years as a museum for visitors.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Three of the most notable Andalusi astronomers were Ibn Tufail (d.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] 1198), and Nur ad-Din al-Bitruji (Alpetragius; d.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] All lived around the same time and focused their astronomical works on critiquing and revising Ptolemaic astronomy and the problem of the equant in his astronomical model.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Instead, they accepted Aristotle's model and promoted the theory of homocentric spheres.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Al-Bitruji is believed to have studied under Ibn Tufail and Bitruji's *Book on Cosmology* (*Kitab fi al-hay'a*) built on Ibn Tufail's work, as well as that of Ibn Rushd, Ibn Bajja, and Maimonides.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] The book's goal was "to overcome the physical difficulties inherent in the geometrical models of Ptolemy's *Almagest* and to describe the cosmos in agreement with Aristotelian or Neoplatonic physics," which it succeeded in doing to an extent.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Bitruji's book set a precedent of criticising the *Almagest* in future works in the field of astronomy.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Although Ibn Rushd originally trained and practiced as a jurist, he was exposed to astronomy—possibly through Ibn Tufail—and became a renowned scientist in the field.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] His most popular work was his *Summary of the Almagest*, but he also published shorter works discussing Aristotle's planetary theories.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Ibn Rushd published writings on philosophy, theology, and medicine throughout his life too, including commentaries on the works of Ibn Sina.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] In addition to writing the important *Book of the Medicine of the Arabs*, Ibn Habib also wrote the *Book on Stars* (*Kirab fi l-nujim*).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] This book included important "teachings on the lunar mansions, the signs of the zodiac, [and] the division of the seasons." In these teachings, Ibn-Habib calculated the phases of the moon and dates of the annual solstices and equinoxes with relative accuracy.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Another important astronomer from al-Andalus was Maslama al-Majriti (d.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] 1007), who played a role in translating and writing about Ptolemy's *Planisphaerium* and *Almagest*.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] He built on the work of older astronomers, like Muhammad ibn Musa al-Khwarizmi, whose astronomical tables he wrote a discussion on and subsequently improved.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] 1087) had many influential astronomical successes, as shown by Copernicus's recognition of him in his *On the Revolutions of the Heavenly Spheres* five centuries later.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Along with other astronomers, he undertook extensive work to edit the Toledan Zij astronomical tables.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] He also accurately calculated the motion of the solar apogee to be 12.04 seconds per year, which is relatively close to today's calculation of 11.8 seconds per year.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Other important scientific advances in al-Andalus occurred in the field of agronomy.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] These advances were in part facilitated by technological innovations in irrigation systems.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] State organised, large-scale irrigation projects provided water to city baths, mosques, gardens, residential homes, and governing palaces, such as the al-Hambra and its gardens in Granada.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Collective, peasant-built irrigation infrastructure also played an important role, especially in agriculture.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Many of these irrigation techniques, especially those utilised by peasants, were brought to al-Andalus by migrating Berber and Arab tribes.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Although some irrigation projects built on existing Roman infrastructure, most of al-Andalus's irrigation systems were new projects built separate from old Roman aqueducts.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] However, there is some debate about this among scholars.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] One notable agriculturalist was Ibn al-'Awwam, who wrote the *Book of Agriculture*.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] This book contains 34 chapters about various aspects of agriculture and animal husbandry, including discussions of over 580 different types of plants and how to treat plant diseases.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p01] Other agronomic innovations in al-Andalus include the cultivation of the pomegranate from Syria, which has since become the namesake and ubiquitous symbol of the city of Granada, as well as the first attempt to create a botanical garden near Córdoba by 'Abd al-Rahman I.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The society of al-Andalus was made up of three main religious groups: Muslims, Christians, and Jews.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The Muslims, although united on the religious level, had several ethnic divisions, the main being the distinction between the Arabs and the Berbers.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The Arab elite regarded non-Arab Muslims as second-class citizens; and they were particularly scornful of the Berbers.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The ethnic structure of al-Andalus consisted of Arabs at the top of the social scale followed by, in descending order, Berbers, Muladies, Mozarabes, and Jews.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Each of these communities inhabited distinct neighbourhoods in the cities.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] In the 10th century a massive conversion of Christians took place, and *muladies* formed the majority of Muslims.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Thomas Glick claims that Muladies, together with other Muslims, comprised eighty per cent of the population of al-Andalus by 1100.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Mozarabs were Christians who had long lived under Muslim and Arab rule, adopting many Arab customs, art and architecture, and words, while still maintaining their Christian and Latin rituals and their own Romance languages.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The Jewish population worked mainly as tax collectors, in trade, or as doctors or ambassadors.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] At the end of the 15th century there were about 50,000 Jews in Granada and roughly 100,000 in the whole of Islamic Iberia, which had been reduced to the territory of the Emirate of Granada.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Non-Muslims were given the status of *ahl al-dhimma* (people under protection), with adult men paying a "Jizya" tax equal to one dinar per year with exemptions for the elderly and the disabled.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Those who were neither Christians nor Jews, such as pagans, were given the status of *Majus*.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The treatment of non-Muslims in the Caliphate has been a subject of considerable debate among scholars and commentators, especially those interested in drawing parallels to the co-existence of Muslims and non-Muslims in the modern world.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Jews constituted more than five per cent of the population.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Al-Andalus was a key centre of Jewish life during the early Middle Ages, produced important scholars and was one of the most stable and wealthy Jewish communities.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Southern Iberia became an asylum for the oppressed Jews of other countries.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Under the Almoravids and the Almohads, there may have been intermittent persecution of Jews, but sources are extremely scarce and do not give a clear picture though the situation appears to have deteriorated after 1160.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Muslim pogroms against Jews in al-Andalus occurred in Córdoba (1011) and in Granada (1066).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] However, massacres of *dhimmis* are believed to be rare in Islamic history.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The Almohads, who had taken control of the Almoravids' Maghribi and Andalusi territories by 1147, far surpassed the Almoravides in fundamentalist outlook, and treated the non-Muslims harshly.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Faced with the choice of either death or conversion, many Jews and Christians emigrated.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Some, such as the family of Maimonides, fled east to more tolerant Muslim lands.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Many ethnicities and religions co-existed in al-Andalus, each of which contributed to its intellectual prosperity.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Literacy in Islamic Iberia was far more widespread than in many other nations in the West of the time.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Though the number of the early inhabitants of al-Andalus after the 7th-century conquest was small, many native Iberian inhabitants converted to Islam, known as *Muwalladun* in Arabic or *Muladíes* in Spanish.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] By 1000, according to Ronald Segal, some 5,000,000 of Iberia's 7,000,000 inhabitants, most of them descended from indigenous Iberian converts, were Muslim.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] There were also Sub-Saharan Africans who had been absorbed into al-Andalus to be used as soldiers and slaves.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The Berber and the sub-Saharan African soldiers were known as "tangerines" because they were imported through the Mediterranean coastal city of Tangier.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] In the 11th century, the Hindu-Arabic numeral system (base 10) had reached Europe via al-Andalus through Spanish Muslims, together with knowledge of astronomy and instruments like the astrolabe, which was first imported by Gerbert of Aurillac.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] For that reason, the numerals came to be known in Europe as Arabic numerals despite their origins in India.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] From the earliest days, the Umayyads wanted to be seen as intellectual rivals to the Abbasids and for Córdoba to have libraries and educational institutions to that of their rival, Baghdad.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Although there was a clear rivalry between the two powers, there was freedom to travel between the two caliphates, which helped spread new ideas and innovations over time.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Multilingual households were an attested phenomenon.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Initially, most of the population spoke Romance dialects.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The dialects of Iberian Romance that were spoken in al-Andalus are collectively referred to as Andalusi Romance or Mozarabic.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] What is hypothesised about these dialects is based on sparse evidence, including Romance topographical and personal names and the *kharjas* of some **muwaššaḥ** poetry.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Arabic arrived with the Umayyad conquest of Hispania in 711 and spread gradually over the following centuries, primarily through conversion to Islam.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The vernacular varieties of Arabic spoken in al-Andalus, referred to as Andalusi Arabic, were Maghrebi Arabic dialects influenced by their contact with Romance, just as Arabic influenced Spanish.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] By about 1260, following the Almohad period, most Christians had migrated to the north and Muslim territories in Iberia were reduced to the Emirate of Granada, in which more than 90% of the population had converted to Islam and Arabic-Romance bilingualism seems to have largely disappeared.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The literary traditions of Hebrew—which was used for prayer and ceremonial writings, but not for oral communication—experienced a revolution through contact with Arabic and its literary traditions.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Consuelo López Morillas writes that Jews in al-Andalus "wrote Hebrew poetry using Arabic prosodic models and adopted nearly the entire range of Arabic poetic genres and stylistic devices in Hebrew," looking to Biblical Hebrew as a source for literary expression as Muslims looked to Quranic Arabic.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Berber languages, referred to in contemporary sources as *al-lisān al-gharbī* (اللسان الغربي, Arabic for 'the western tongue'), were especially present in periods of Berber rule, particularly under the Almoravids and Almohads.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Under Almohad rule, it was compulsory to deliver the *khuṭba* (sermon) at Friday prayer in Arabic and *al-lisān al-gharbī*.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] In al-Andalus, there are 11,831 known scholars who were active and 13,730 known works that were written or transmitted from the eighth to fifteenth centuries.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Of these scholars, those who are well known and remembered in the West, such as Ibn Rushd, Ibn Hazm, or Ibn Arabi, are not necessarily the same scholars that are remembered in Islamic culture, such as Abū ʿUmar b. ʿAbd al-Barr, Abū l-Walīd al-Bājī, Ibn ʿAtịyya, Ibn al-ʿArīf, or Abū Isḥāq aš-Šāṭibī.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Poetry was considered the prime literary genre in Arabic.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Traditional forms of Arabic poetry from the Mashriq, or Muslim East, especially the monometer, monorhyme *qaṣīda* and the prosimetric *maqāma*, were adopted in al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The major Andalusi innovation in poetry was the 'rhyme revolution' embodied in the 10th-11th century strophic song form called the *muwaššaḥ* ('girdled'; pl.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The *muwaššaḥ* features a complex rhyme scheme usually containing five *aghsān* ('branches'; sing.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] *ghusn*), with uniform rhyme within each strophe, interspersed with *asmāṭ* ('threads for stringing pearls'; sing.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] *simṭ*) with common rhyme throughout the song, as well as a terminal *kharja*, the song's final *simṭ*, which could be in a different language.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Andalusi *zajal* was strophic poetry in Andalusi vernacular Arabic, usually associated with Ibn Quzman.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Andalusi strophic poetry had an impact on poetic expression in Western Europe, especially the Old Occitan/Provençal lyric of the troubadours, and in the wider Muslim world.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The music of al-Andalus is part of an influential musical tradition.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Ziryab, a poet and musician, who came from the Abbasid Caliphate and arrived in Córdoba in 822, played a role in Andalusi music as well as other aspects of Andalusi culture.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Poetic forms such as the *muwashshah* and its *kharja*, the *nawba*, and the *zajal* are prominent in Andalusi music.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The historian Said al-Andalus wrote that Caliph Abd-ar-Rahman III had collected libraries of books and granted patronage to scholars of medicine and "ancient sciences".
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Later, *al-Mustansir* (Al-Hakam II) went yet further, building a university and libraries in Córdoba.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Córdoba became one of the world's leading centres of medicine and philosophical debate.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] When Al-Hakam's son Hisham II took over, real power was ceded to the *hajib*, al-Mansur Ibn Abi Aamir.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Al-Mansur was a distinctly religious man and disapproved of the sciences of astronomy, logic, and especially of astrology, so much so that many books on these subjects, which had been preserved and collected at great expense by Al-Hakam II, were burned publicly.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] With Al-Mansur's death in 1002, interest in philosophy revived.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Numerous scholars emerged, including Abu Uthman Ibn Fathun, whose masterwork was the philosophical treatise "Tree of Wisdom".
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Maslamah Ibn Ahmad al-Majriti (died 1008) was an outstanding scholar in astronomy and astrology; he was an intrepid traveller who journeyed all over the Islamic world and beyond and kept in touch with the Brethren of Purity.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] He is said to have brought the 51 "Epistles of the Brethren of Purity" to *al-Andalus* and added the compendium to this work, although it is quite possible that it was added later by another scholar with the name al-Majriti.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Another book attributed to al-Majriti is the *Ghayat al-Hakim*, "The Aim of the Sage", which explored a synthesis of Platonism with Hermetic philosophy.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Its use of incantations led the book to be widely dismissed in later years, although the Sufi communities continued to study it.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] A prominent follower of al-Majriti was the philosopher and geometer Abu al-Hakam al-Kirmani who was followed, in turn, by Abu Bakr Ibn al-Sayigh, usually known in the Arab world as Ibn Bajjah, "Avempace".
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The al-Andalus philosopher Averroes (1126–1198) was the founder of the Averroism school of philosophy, and his works and commentaries influenced medieval thought in Western Europe.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Another influential al-Andalus philosopher was Ibn Tufail.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] As Jewish thought in Babylonia declined, the tolerance of *al-Andalus* made it the new centre of Jewish intellectual endeavours.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Poets and commentators like Judah Halevi (1086–1145) and Dunash ben Labrat (920–990) contributed to the cultural life of *al-Andalus*, but the area was even more important to the development of Jewish philosophy.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] In al-Andalus, Jews played a significant role in the medical sphere and achieved prominence as physicians.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Hasdai ibn Shaprut, a Jewish court official and physician in 10th-century Córdoba, was involved in the Arabic translation of Dioscorides' *Materia Medica*, collaborating with both Christian and Muslim scholars.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] In 11th-century Zaragoza, Jonah ibn Janah authored a pharmacological treatise that provided multilingual drug names and detailed discussions of weights and measures used in medicine.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] His contemporary, Jonah ibn Biklārish, compiled a medical dictionary for Zaragoza's rulers, presenting materia medica in tabular form across several languages, including Syriac, Persian, Greek, Latin, and Spanish.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Tzvi Langermann, Andalusian medicine evolved distinctive characteristics and, by the 11th century, increasingly shifted away from eastern Islamic models in favour of closer ties with North African traditions.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The influence of Andalusian medicine is evident in later Jewish figures such as Maimonides (1135–1204), whose teachers were trained in this tradition and who himself adopted its emphasis on holistic, Galenic approaches to care.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] In Córdoba, Abd ar-Rahman I built the Great Mosque of Córdoba in 785.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] It was expanded multiple times up until the 10th century, and after the Reconquista it was converted into a Catholic cathedral.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Its key features include a hypostyle hall with marble columns supporting two-tiered arches, a horseshoe-arch mihrab, ribbed domes, a courtyard (*sahn*) with gardens, and a minaret (later converted into a bell tower).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Abd ar-Rahman III, at the height of his power, began construction of Madinat al-Zahra, a luxurious palace-city to serve as a new capital.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The Umayyads also reconstructed the Roman-era bridge over the Guadalquivir River in Córdoba, while the Almohads later added the Calahorra Tower to the bridge.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The Bab al-Mardum Mosque (later converted to a church) in Toledo is a well-preserved example of a small neighbourhood mosque built at the end of the Caliphate period.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The official workshops of the Caliphate, such as those at Madinat al-Zahra, produced luxury goods for use at court or as gifts for guests, allies, and diplomats, which stimulated artistic production.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Many objects produced in the caliph's workshops later made their way into the collections of museums and Christian cathedrals in Europe.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Among the most famous objects of this period are ivory boxes which are carved with vegetal, figurative, and epigraphic motifs.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Notable surviving examples include the Pyxis of al-Mughira, the Pyxis of Zamora, and the Leyre Casket.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] During the Taifas period, art and culture continued to flourish despite the political fragmentation of al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The Aljaferia Palace of Zaragoza is the most significant palace preserved from this period, featuring complex ornamental arcades and stucco decoration.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] In other cities, a number of important palaces or fortresses were begun or expanded by local dynasties such as the Alcazaba of Málaga and the Alcazaba of Almería.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Other examples of architecture from around this period include the Bañuelo of Granada, an Islamic bathhouse.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] In Seville, Almohad rulers built the Great Mosque of Seville (later transformed into the Cathedral of Seville), which consisted of a hypostyle prayer hall, a courtyard (now known as the *Patio de los Naranjos* or Court of Oranges), and a massive minaret tower now known as the Giralda.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The minaret was later expanded after being converted into a bell tower for the current cathedral.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Almohad architecture promoted new forms and decorative designs such as the multifoil arch and the sebka motif, probably influenced by the Caliphate-period architecture of Córdoba.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Artists and intellectuals took refuge at Granada after the Christian kingdoms expanded significantly in the 13th century.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The palaces of the Alhambra and the Generalife in Granada reflect the culture and art of the last centuries of Muslim rule of al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The complex was begun by Ibn al-Ahmar, the first Nasrid emir, and the last major additions were made during the reigns of Yusuf I (1333–1353) and Muhammad V (1353–1391).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] It integrates buildings and gardens with the natural qualities of the site and is a testament to Andalusi culture and to the skills of the Muslim artisans, craftsmen, and builders of their era.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Nasrid architecture continued the earlier traditions of Andalusi architecture while also synthesising them into its own distinctive style, which had many similarities with contemporary Marinid architecture in North Africa.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] It is characterised by the use of the courtyard as a central space and basic unit around which other halls and rooms were organised.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Courtyards typically had water features at their centre, such as a reflective pool or a fountain.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Decoration was focused on the inside of buildings and was executed primarily with tile mosaics on lower walls and carved stucco on the upper walls.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Geometric patterns, vegetal motifs, and calligraphy were the main types of decorative motifs.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Additionally, "stalactite"-like sculpting, known as muqarnas, was used for three-dimensional features like vaulted ceilings, particularly during the reign of Muhammad V and after.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Numerous examples are found in the early churches of Toledo (e.g. the Church of San Román, 13th century) and in the cities of Aragon such as Zaragoza and Teruel.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Among the most famous examples is the Alcázar of Seville, the former Abbadid and Almohad palace redeveloped by Christian rulers such as Peter of Castile, who in 1364 started adding new Moorish-style sections with the help of Muslim craftsmen from Granada and Toledo.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Some surviving 13th and 14th-century Jewish synagogues were also built (or rebuilt) in Mudéjar style under Christian rule, such as the Synagogue of Santa Maria la Blanca in Toledo (rebuilt in its current form circa 1250), the Synagogue of Córdoba (1315), and the Synagogue of El Tránsito (1355–1357).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Crops produced using irrigation, along with food imported from the Middle East, provided areas around *Andalusī* cities with an agricultural economic sector that was the most advanced in Europe by far, sparking the Arab Agricultural Revolution.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] A variety of foodstuffs, spices and crops were introduced to Spain and Sicily during Arab rule, via the commercial networks of the Islamic world.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] These include sugarcane, rice, cotton, alfalfa, oranges, lemons, apricots, spinach, eggplants, carrots, saffron and bananas.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The Arabs also continued extensive cultivation and production of olive oil (the Spanish words for 'oil' and 'olive'—*aceite* and *aceituna*, respectively—are derived from the Arabic *al-zait*, meaning 'olive juice'), and pomegranates (the heraldic symbol of Granada) from classical Greco-Roman times.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Arabic influence still lingers on in Spanish cuisine through these fruits, vegetables, spices and cooking and agricultural techniques.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] These structures are still found in Andalusia province, particularly in Granada.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The confection *alfajor* (supposedly from الفاخر) has its origins in al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Important rulers such as Abd al-Rahman III, al-Hakam II, Hisham II, and al-Mu-tamid openly chose boys as sexual partners, and kept catamites.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Homosexual prostitution was widespread, and its customers came from higher levels of society than those of heterosexual prostitutes." The verses of Ibn Quzman describe an openly bisexual lifestyle.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Andalusi anthologies of poetry such as the *Rāyāt al-mubarrizīn wa-ghāyāt al-mumayyazīn* are known in part for their homoerotic and "abundant pederastic poetry".
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Such themes were also found in the Sephardic Jewish poetry of the time.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] In the book *Medieval Iberia: An Encyclopedia*, Daniel Eisenberg describes homosexuality as "a key symbolic issue throughout the Middle Ages in Iberia", stating that "in al-Andalus homosexual pleasures were much indulged in by the intellectual and political elite.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Both pederasty and love between adult males are found.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Although homosexual practices were never officially condoned, prohibitions against them were rarely enforced, and usually there was not even a pretense of doing so." Male homosexual relations allowed nonprocreative sexual practices and were not seen as a form of identity.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Very little is known about the homosexual behaviour of women.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Slavery existed in Muslim al-Andalus as well as in the Christian kingdoms, and both sides of the religious border followed the custom of not enslaving people of their own religion.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Consequently, Muslims were enslaved in Christian lands, while Christians and other non-Muslims were enslaved in al-Andalus.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The Moors imported white Christian slaves from the 8th century until the end of the Reconquista in the late 15th century.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The slaves were exported from the Christian section of Spain, as well as Eastern Europe (*Saqaliba*).
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Saqaliba slavery in al-Andalus was especially prominent in the Caliphate of Córdoba where white slaves constituted most of the administrative personnel in the courts and palaces.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The slaves of the Caliph were often European saqaliba slaves trafficked from Northern or Eastern Europe.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] While male saqaliba could be given work in a number of tasks, such as offices in the kitchen, falconry, mint, textile workshops, the administration or the royal guard (in the case of harem guards, they were castrated), female saqaliba were placed in the harem.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The harem could contain thousands of slave concubines; the harem of Abd al-Rahman I consisted of 6,300 women.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] They were appreciated for their light skin.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] The concubines (jawaris) were educated in accomplishments to please their master, and many became known and respected for their knowledge in a variety of subjects from music to medicine.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Jawaris concubines who gave birth to a child attained the status of an *umm walad*, which meant that they could no longer be sold and were to be set free after the death of her master.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] As Andalusi cities were conquered by Leon, Castile, and other Christian Spanish kingdoms, Christian monarchs such as Alfonso X of Castile started translating the mountainous libraries of al-Andalus into Latin.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] These libraries contained translations of Ancient Greek texts, as well as new ones made by Muslims in the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] That, combined with the interaction with Muslims during the Crusades, and the Fall of Constantinople introducing Greek scholars to the west, helped launch the Renaissance.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Scientists and philosophers such as Averroes and Al-Zahrawi (fathers of rationalism and surgery, respectively) heavily inspired the Renaissance, and their ideas are still world renowned to this day.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Al Andalus has also left art and architecture and has some of the best preserved Islamic Golden Age architecture in the world, with examples including the Cathedral of Córdoba, the Alhambra, the Giralda and many more.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] As a result of the Reconquista and fall of many important Andalusi cities, substantial numbers of Andalusi migrated to the Maghreb where they found place at the courts of Maghrebi rulers.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] Many of the elite Andalusi immigrants were Arabs.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] For a variety of reasons, "Andalusi" came to be almost synonymous with "Arab" in the Maghreb.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] In the Iberian Peninsula, many Muslims were forced to convert to Christianity, particularly in the latter period of the Reconquista and following the decrees of 1502 and 1526.
[src:asida/al-andalus-p02] These converts and their descendants, known as Moriscos, remained under intense persecution until their expulsion in the early 17th century.
[src:asida/asida] Asida is particularly common in Sudan, Morocco, Libya, Algeria, Tunisia, Yemen, Ethiopia, Eritrea, and the rest of the Middle East.
[src:asida/asida] Often served during religious holidays such as Mawlid and Eid, it is also served during other traditional ceremonies—for example, those accompanying the birth of a child, such as the *‘aqīqah*, the cutting of the hair of a newborn seven days after birth.
[src:asida/asida] A simple, yet rich dish, often eaten without other complementary dishes, it is traditionally served at breakfast and is also given to women in labor.
[src:asida/asida] The name *asida* is derived from the Arabic root عصد (ʿ-ṣ-d), associated with twisting or kneading.
[src:asida/asida] One of the earliest documented recipes for asida is found in a tenth century Arabic cookbook by Ibn Sayyar al-Warraq called *Kitab al-Ṭabīḫ* (Arabic: كتاب الطبيخ, *The Book of Dishes*).
[src:asida/asida] It was described as a thick pudding of dates cooked with clarified butter (*samn*).
[src:asida/asida] A recipe for asida was also mentioned in an anonymous Hispano-Muslim cookbook dating to the 13th century.
[src:asida/asida] In the 13th and 14th centuries, in the mountainous region of the Rif along the Mediterranean coast of Morocco, a flour made from lightly grilled barley was used in place of wheat flour.
[src:asida/asida] A recipe for asida that adds argan seed oil was documented by Leo Africanus (c.
[src:asida/asida] 1465–1550), the Arab explorer known as Hasan al-Wazan in the Arab world.
[src:asida/asida] According to the French scholar Maxime Rodinson, asida were typical foods among the Bedouin of pre-Islamic and, probably, later times.
[src:asida/asida] In the old city of Fez, vendors sell squares of cold semolina pudding sprinkled with sugar and cinnamon, usually consumed by children after school.
[src:asida/asida] The Libyan variation of asida is served with a sweet syrup, usually date or carob syrup (rub), but also with honey, as well as melted butter around the asida itself.
[src:asida/asida] Asida (Aseeda) is made primarily as a dessert by Palestinians.
[src:asida/asida] It serves as a both a comfort food and a dish to mark special occasions.
[src:asida/asida] The dessert version is served with honey or date syrup, and for special occasions might see the addition of sauteed nuts and cinnamon.
[src:asida/asida] A savory dish also called asida but consisting of stewed wheat berries with lamb is made in at least one village in Palestine at times of mourning, attesting to the uniqueness and specificity of local food customs.
[src:asida/asida] The Tunisian version of this dish is served with either a mixture of honey and butter or a hot chili pepper paste (harissa).
[src:asida/asida] The latter is more common later in the day and the former earlier.
[src:asida/asida] Asida is also commonly consumed with carob syrup or date syrup in southern parts of Tunisia.
[src:asida/asida] Aseedah or aseed (Arabic: عصيدة) is one of the staple dishes in Yemen and is usually served for lunch, dinner, or breakfast.
[src:asida/asida] Its ingredients include wholemeal wheat, boiling water, and salt as needed.
[src:asida/asida] A pot of water is placed on high heat until boiling.
[src:asida/asida] Slowly, handfuls of wholemeal wheat are added and then mixed quickly with a large wooden spoon to avoid forming lumps.
[src:asida/asida] The process is repeated until the mixture is thick.
[src:asida/asida] Traditionally the cook lowers the pot to the floor where they hold the pot with their feet and stir vigorously.
[src:asida/asida] Finally, the hot, steaming dough is shaped using bare oiled hands and usually placed in a wide, wooden bowl.
[src:asida/asida] Sometimes a depression is made in the middle of the shaped aseedah into which a hot chili tomato paste can be added or helba, a fenugreek mixture made with parsley and garlic.
[src:asida/asida] Lamb or a chicken stock is then poured around the aseedah.
[src:asida/asida] Aseedah can also be made using white, bleached wheat.
[src:asida/asida] Honey can be used instead of stock and chili/helba.
[src:asida/asida] It is a meal, using only boiled water, flour, and some salt.
[src:asida/asida] Typically it is smothered in beef soup or chicken or even lamb.
[src:asida/asida] It is usually served hot and eaten with hands or spoons.
[src:asida/asida] Aseed is eaten particularly at lunchtime and during Ramadan.
[src:asida/asida] The Ethiopian version of this dish is called genfo in Amharic.
[src:asida/asida] It is served with Ethiopian ghee (called niter kibbeh), berbere (an Ethiopian spice mix), yogurt, or even milk.
[src:asida/asida] It is popular during Ramadan, and is often served with a meat-and-tomato sauce.
